description:
Windows Apps London (formerly Windows Phone User Group) exists to help UK based developers who are interested in Microsoft’s Windows & Windows Phone platforms learn from and with each other.

We hold monthly meetings in London (and occasionally elsewhere) where there are talks, demos and discussions. Plus swag, prizes, pizza and beer!

Whether you’re new to phone/mobile development or have been doing it for years you’re most welcome to come to a meeting.

WinAppsLdn is an independent group and does not charge for membership or meeting attendance. We simply ask that you come willing to participate in discussion or share your knowledge and that you register if you’re planning on coming to a meeting.

 

We held our first meeting in July 2010 and have had meetings most months since. You can see details of past meetings at http://windowsapps.london/meetings/

description:
Kanban Coaching Exchange (KCE)

The KCE is intended to be a really great place to learn, get those burning questions off your chest and to make new friends. It follows in the footsteps of the Agile Coaching Exchange (ACE) which often has Kanban specific questions and topics, the KCE will provide a Kanban focused forum.

We pride ourselves in giving back to the Kanban community and so these exchanges are about:

  • Connecting Kanban practitioners so that they can collaborate and work together in the future
  • Creating a learning environment
  • Providing a place for newer practitioners and coaches to seek support
  • Exchanging coaching skills and experiences
  • Developing new concepts collaboratively that we can use when coaching
  • Developing ideas that will support the discipline of coaching
  • Having fun, sharing, and collaboration
  • Improving the understanding of Kanban in the wider community

The target audience is you, peers that you work with or have worked with, Kanban practitioners, and anybody with potential to be coaches or good Kanban practitioners. Please feel free to bring others along, especially people from your current workplace/engagement who could benefit from this kind of sharing event.

The format will be a talk by an invited speaker, followed by open discussion based on what the group feels would be the best topics to spend our time on.

description:
Innovation Warehouse is a community for entrepreneurs working on high-growth, high-impact startup businesses. We are located in London, on top of Smithfields Market, and opened in 2010. Formed by a group of entrepreneurs and angel investors in collaboration with the City of London Corporation, Innovation Warehouse provides coworking space, a community and runway for businesses looking to achieve sustainability and high growth.

Our activities are: Coworking - with the Hot Desking, Shared Office Space and private offices combined in a productive environment; Investment - with an incubator, extensive angel network; Events - we organise and host meet-ups, hackathons, training sessions, developers' job fairs; and an ongoing Business Accelerator.

Innovation Warehouse offers various membership options and benefits tailored on each start-up's needs. You can only find all of them out by paying us a visit... If you're an aspiring entrepreneur, a co-founder or an investor and are looking for a Community, we are the perfect place to grow.

This group is a forum to find and share information on any aspect of the Innovation Warehouse, such as collaborative business model, coworking space, events, activities, participation, programs, investment, mentoring, microlending.

description:
Data is growing in size and complexity. Increasing velocity, volume and variety of data are driving new database technologies and techniques of data analysis. NOSQL databases are becoming more popular and widely accepted. This is leading to a disruption in the database market and a fragmentation of database solutions.

At DeNormalised we want to bring together people who are interested in keeping up to date with the evolving landscape of data persistance and analysis. Our meetups will consist of a number of short talks on a range of topics including NOSQL, big data and data science.

The meetups are designed to give broad exposure and inspire. If you build, maintain or manage software that produces data, there's a good chance you'll get something out of this group.

Come along, learn and share.

description:
Excited about the Raspberry Pi??

We are!

We hope that this hardware will help usher in a new generation of hackers (used in the purest sense of the term) and give even the most disadvantaged a chance to become beguiled by technology! The trouble is, there's no point sticking a circuit board in the kids hands unless there's a community out there with know how.

The aim of this club is to have semi regular meetups in a relaxed setting where we can show off our latest hacks or help each other learn.

There's also a facebook page for general chit-chat and somewhere to share your Vids & Pics and other news.

We are part of GeekZone, a larger community organisation that connects, geeks, nerds, hackers and anyone who believes that one can do great things by bringing great people together.

Become a full GeekZone member by joining Geek.Zone! It's the best way to catch up with geeky friends and news! Don't miss out! Join now!

Take a look at our...

WWW | Facebook | Twitter

Looking forward to meeting you!

description:

description:
The worlds of hackers and journalists are coming together as reporting goes digital and Internet companies become media empires.

Journalists call themselves "hacks," someone who can churn out words in any situation. Hackers use the digital equivalent of duct tape to whip out code. Hacker-journalists try and bridge the two worlds.

This group is to bring all these people together -- those who are working to help people make sense of their world. It's for hackers exploring technologies to filter and visualize information, and for journalists who use technology to find and tell stories. In the age of information overload, all their work has become even more crucial.

This group aims to help members find inspiration and think in new directions, bringing together potential collaborators for projects and new ventures.

Please also check out our blog at http://hackshackers.com Help us build the future of media!

description:
We Love Social Media. We love it, we love it, we love it and all it can do to bring the world closer together. Whether its businesses closer to their customers, or governments closer to their citizens.

We want to share this love with you in this Love Social Media Meet Up group. Your educational source for Social Media. Love Social Media’s aim is to educate entrepreneurs, traditional publicists, and business owners on marketing themselves online to improve online reputation, increase sales and improve search engine rankings. We teach our clients from the basics in social media to implementing social media for their business to take full advantage of all the benefits that social media has to offer.

We explore how social media has enabled new ways for organisations to connect both internally and externally. Our meetings will focus on practical applications of Social Media tools and platforms like Facebook, Twitter, YouTube, Google+, Pinterest, LinkedIn, blogging and more. We will talk about Viral Marketing and Social Media in all kinds of business applications - Media Business, Technology, Finance, eCommerce, Customer Care; Social Media for sales teams and Marketers, event organisers and HR and internal communications. Love Social Media is here to educate and facilitate meaningful discussions for eager businesses on the latest social media trends, tips and tricks, and specific techniques to improve your reputation and your relationship with your customers using social media.

We believe love is about passion. If you are passionate about social media, you have to join our community. In this meet up group you can engage with other Lovers and share everything you love about social media.

Join us today!

description:
The London Video Meetup is London's premier gathering of online video creators, entrepreneurs, experts and developers.

The London Video Meetup is for anyone based in London who would like to socialise and network with people working in the online video community. Whether you're a video content producer, an organisation using video to share your message, a video solutions provider, a developer, or just interested in the power of video to market and expand your business, increase learning results or productivity, this meetup is for you!

We meet monthly in London to showcase and discuss the emerging trends of our industry, share experiences and practices of using video in education, communication, marketing and more. Each month we'll have 2-4 lightning presentations followed by bi-directional Q&A. Our goal is to bring the local online video community from leading media & entertainment companies, top tier universities, enterprises, small businesses and publishers gather to learn, connect, and consider the state of web video and media management and to inspire and help each other succeed by sharing our collective experience.

We are London's Online Video Community, come and join the buzz!

description:
WP-hooked is a forum/meetup for WordPress core contributors, theme and plugin developers to get together and share issues, ideas and tips about WordPress.

If your main interaction with WordPress is through the admin console, if it's something that you install and configure rather than build then this meetup probably isn't for you. There's a long-running "WordPress London" meetup which has a much broader scope and will probably give you what you need.

If on the other hand you relish the thought of getting stuck into writing some php code, you can handle using the theme editor on a live site as an option, or the thought of managing your own servers isn't terrifying, then you've probably come to the right place.

The format of the meetups has yet to be decided, and will evolve as we learn what works and what doesn't.

We welcome speakers from any sphere who can add something to our development

description:
Hi Big Data enthusiasts my names Nathan,

I'm a regular attendee at many of the Big Data meet ups decided this rapidly expanding space is in need of some hiring solutions to help both employers and employees find suitable matches in confidence. So please, if you’re on here or your employee is it doesn’t mean you/they are looking but you may be contacted by someone who is!

I hope people will just use it just like any other job board but it’s free and with the benefit of it being our market specific and having a meet up within. The meet ups will be like a job fair and an opportunity to network and learn from each other.

The purpose of this group will be to aid and benefit those seeking a new opportunity in Big Data or as an employer, where you can find your next hire or advertise your job in our discussions column. I would be interested in speaking to Universities and trainers who could help us educate the next Data Scientists too. 

Be your search active or passive, I hope this group will help you satisfy all your needs. For any help or advice please feel free to contact me: Nathan.laidlaw@gcsltd.comor call 01189 563 900.

Follow us on Twitter: @bigdatajobs1

description:
Welcome to the Spring of Code group!

We are a civic engagement community creating digital tools to improve democracy and public services.

    This Civic Tech project is based on the ethics of open data, free software, open source and creative commons. So join up, and shout out what's missing from the online tools already out there or how we can make them work better together.

    We advocate for a user centred-design approach as the only way to design digital products and services that people will actually use.

    Who should join?

    Improving democracy isn't just for Developers, it is everyone's mission. To design digital projects that address the needs of users, we need many skillsets involved to analyse, re-think, design, prototype and develop the whole experience. We need service designers, domain experts, UX/UI Designers etc. to bring the right level of expertise to projects.

    What happens in a meeting?

    People meet people, pitch each other projects, share their war stories, talk about product needs, get essential user feedback

    What happens between meetings?

    People buddy up on projects, hack, design, get creative and update on site their progress.

    Do you have a Code of conduct?

    Yes we follow the excellent 18F Code of Conduct.

    ________________________

    So join fellow SpringofCoders right now and start participating in an active, skilled and friendly community.

description: After seeing so many successful financial Meetup groups in the US we have noticed the absence of something similar over here. Therefore we thought that London as a financial capital must have one too. So we decided to start our own financial meetup group for London. This group aims for everyone from the industry, whether you work for a hedge fund, a bank, a financial service provider, academia, your own business or you are just passionate about finance, financial engineering, modelling or trading. This group should give likeminded people the opportunity to exchange ideas, spot talent, offer talent, extend your network and have good conversations in a friendly environment. Our meetups will take place in central London in alternating venues, anywhere between Mayfair to Aldgate to Canary Wharf and will mostly be afterwork events.

description:
Founded by The People Who Share this is a collaborative community dedicated to connecting, championing and building the #SharingEconomy. This diverse group that includes social entrepreneurs, innovators, business leaders, economists, strategic thinkers, investors and sociologists.

Working together online and offline we are weaving together the broad threads of the Sharing Economy, including Collaborative Consumption, Shared Value, Peer2Peer services, Co-creation, Co-production Cradle2Cradle, crowd funding, crowdsourcing, Crowdsharing, the Co-operatives movement, new economics and social media.

Join up to participate in:  Thought provoking, action based Sharing Economy events  Discussions, debates and research to find solutions for main streaming the Sharing Economy  Opportunities to collaborate and innovate  Sharing conversations, insights, skills and experience

description:
Big Data Brighton is a community of data enthusiasts who share an interest in the potential that data has to change the way we live, make smarter decisions and improve the way we run businesses.



We organise speaker events, discussions and hackathons around once a quarter that are free for all members to attend. The events are curated around a theme or topic and we welcome suggestions on what members would like to see covered.



Our aim is to program events that appeal to all backgrounds and not just data professionals. We meet at a variety of venues across Brighton and always make sure that there is time to share a drink and chat before and after the speaker slots.



Please get in touch with your ideas and we hope to see you at our next meetup!

description:
What is TechMeetups?

TechMeetups has been setup to create a global network of Tech communities from San Francisco to Sydney. We believe that Tech communities are isolated and great things can be achieved if we connect within our cities and outside our borders. Our goal is to create a global Tech cluster of over 50 inter-connected Tech communities by 2015.

Our global community started out with the launch of the London Silicon Roundabout Tech community in December 2010. Following it's success in becoming one of the city's fastest growing groups, we have launched TechMeetups communities in the following locations:

Europe:London, Berlin, Lisbon, Manchester, Paris, 

Amsterdam, Stockholm, Dublin, Munich, Vienna, Brussels, 

Copenhagen & Barcelona

USA:New York,Dallas,Miami &San Francisco 

Asia:Bangalore, Bangkok, Mumbai & Singapore

Others: Sydney 


You can see our latest list of communitieshere.

Why become a member of TechMeetups?

Anyone who is thinking about starting their own software or web company and wants to bounce ideas off each other and meet potential partners or investors are welcome to join this group!

Our aim is to connect the various tech communities to help our members network, connect, invest and launch products in the hottest technology clusters. We plan to organise monthly meetups to cover various technology subjects that are of interest to our members.

• GET INVOLVED IN EVENTS WORLDWIDE on TechMeetups!


Check out all upcoming events in all our communities and promote your company in one of them!

SPONSOR| PRESENT| MENTOR


• POST YOUR STARTUP JOBS at TechStartupJobs!

Recruiting ? Wanting to hire that perfect team? Post your jobs on TechStartupJobs and/or take part inTechStartupJobs Fair to attract the right talent to your company.

description:
The worlds of hackers and journalists are coming together as reporting goes digital and Internet companies become media empires.

Journalists call themselves "hacks," someone who can churn out words in any situation. Hackers use the digital equivalent of duct tape to whip out code. Hacker-journalists try and bridge the two worlds.

This group is to bring all these people together -- those who are working to help people make sense of their world. It's for hackers exploring technologies to filter and visualize information, and for journalists who use technology to find and tell stories. In the age of information overload, all their work has become even more crucial.

This group aims to help members find inspiration and think in new directions, bringing together potential collaborators for projects and new ventures. Please also check out our blog at http://hackshackers.com

Help us build the future of media!

description:
A regular Meetup group for software developers who care about and take pride in what they do and how they do it.  Modelled on the London Software Craftsmanship Community, I hope to bring some of their success to the Cambridge software community.

Software Craftsmanship has grown out of Agile, with many of the leading lights in the Craftsmanship movement being the founders of the Agile movement as well.

The Software Craftsmanship Manifesto describes the movement as follows:

As aspiring Software Craftsmen we are raising the bar of professional software development by practicing it and helping others learn the craft. Through this work we have come to value:

• Not only working software, but also well-crafted software

• Not only responding to change, but also steadily adding value

• Not only individuals and interactions, but also a community of professionals

• Not only customer collaboration, but also productive partnerships

That is, in pursuit of the items on the left we have found the items on the right to be indispensable.

© 2009, the undersigned.  This statement may be freely copied in any form, but only in its entirety through this notice.

Through this group, I hope to tackle the third point from the manifesto and create and encourage a community of professionals in the Cambridge area.

description:
Architecture begins where engineering ends.

(Walter Gropius)

Hello fellow architects...

This meetup-group is about software-/system-architecture.

We will talk about different technologies and different methodologies, discuss current hypes, compare project types, learn from each other's experience, etc.

The 'system architect' role is not dead. It is still one of the most important roles in the development of complex software system. When you are building simple applications you might not need a system architect, but when the requirements, infrastructure, team structure is more complicated then your project might fail without having the right architect on board.

A system architect needs a different skill- and mind-set than a software developer. He must be business analyst, IT manager, project manager, software developer at the same time. In addition to that he must understand system design principles and technologies like scalability, fault tolerance, distributed computing, etc.

I hope we can form a group of architects here to support each other in our job. I am working usually in server side, ultra-low latency projects in finance (like trading systems, algorithmic trading), but architects from other industries and areas are, of course, welcome as well.

I prepared already a few talks about the architect-role itself and about a few key technologies.

To make this group a success we need, of course, more members. So, please, spread the word. :)

 

Regards

Timo Kramer

description:
The aim of the group is to provide a basic grounding in various programming languages, technologies and practices including Java, JavaScript, Android, iOS, Swift, PHP, Ruby, Groovy, test automation,agile development, etc.

You should join this group if you are new to software development and/or want to learn/share knowledge on how to develop software in various programming languages in a fun, friendly environment. To make it even more fun, bring a friend along.

Our tutors are experienced, practicing software engineers with many years of experience in various industries with a shared passion for coaching and sharing their knowledge with aspiring developers like you.

If you are totally new to programming, we encourage you to signup up to a “Computer Programming Overview” session to get an introduction to programming languages in general before deciding which language you will like to focus on.

Happy Coding!

description: Wanting to learn how to write apps for the Android platform and not finding a meetup group, I decided to form this group. My 25 years software development experience has taught me that a small team of focused people from diverse backgrounds with a common aim always make further progress than an individual. You should join us, if you have good PC and internet literacy, a passion for software development, little or no experience of Android, and a windows laptop. A computer science degree is not a requirement to join. This meetup group doesn't prepare you to step straight into an Android developer role. It's more about giving a basic understanding and confidence to get started developing with Android and to have better conversations with Android developers. If you have missed previous sessions, please feel free to come along and start working through the exercises from earlier meet ups at your own pace and ask for help from more experience group members.

description:
We are the largest London based freelance co-working and events group on Meetup!

We are a community of freespirited freelancers and independent businesses. We organise pop up co-working events which we manage through the Meetup group.  You can find us online at  http://www.kindredhq.com/

We’re really happy to announce that our events programme has just got bigger! Our free KindredHQ coworking Jelly meetups are very popular, and are where you can get on with work in conducive and productive environments, whilst at the same time being around fellow Kindred spirits.  We've been running up to 5 a week across central London and we've now expanded to other locations across the UK and Europe.

Working independently is great but without a traditional company structure behind you it can mean that you miss out on essential support. It can also be a lonely place. Companies are struggling to cope with a workforce that demands ever greater flexibility. KindredHQ solves that by providing emotional and practical support through its community, and works with partners to to deliver innovative ways of replicating those company benefits, without losing your free spirit identity.

description:
This is a meetup about the use of social data.

Like me you may be wanting to use Social data (aka Social media data, big data, unstructured data) to drive insight.

You may be asking questions like:

    What social data should I use and why?

    What can I learn from others who have used social data successfully in their organization?

    What are the key trends in the use of social data?

    Where can I meet with social data publishers face to face?

    What tools can I leverage to analyze?

    How do I integrate social data into my organization?

It's all very well hooking into the Twitter streams and collecting a bunch of Facebook likes but what do we do with the data when we've got it?

So no matter whether you're a budding social media marketing guru, a data scientist, a Chief Data Officer, or a product czar - this meetup is for you.

description:
UX Crunch 


For more information follow us on twitter @theuxcrunch or check out our website www.theuxcrunch.co.uk 

The UX Crunch is London’s largest user experience, networking events and conferences monthly. User 
experience is one of the hottest debatable subjects within the digital world with networking and 
learning key to UX professionals keen to develop their careers.


 In a contract-heavy market, it’s always great to network with hiring managers and meet potential 
connections that could help you secure your next contract.  We approach creating networking events in 
a unique way, showcasing various companies’ user experience and knowledge by hosting our events at 
various venues around London. We aim to create a new phenomenon within digital networking, making 
cutting edge events and opening possibilities of collaboration within the UX community.


Our events often offer free drinks and food as well as some of the most inspirational user experience 
guest speakers in the industry. We welcome people who are looking to get in UX and find out more 
about the area. Recruiters and hiring managers are also welcome and we encourage jobs and 
opportunity networking in an ever-changing and evolving industry.  


Host an event 


We are always looking for major companies to host events. Hosting is free, however you will be 
expected to provide food and drink for the attendees as well as a space large enough to hold more than 
60 people. 


Hosting an event is a great way of getting exposure to a huge user experience audience. This helps 
promote your brand name, encourages people to join your organisation and gives you a great way of 
promoting to your clients/customers. Those hosting the UX Crunch can promote the event on their 
social media platforms to demonstrate support for the UX community and you take pride in your 
website’s usability. 

For more information, contact info@innovate-event.co.uk


Sponsor UX Crunch 


UX Crunch is Europe’s largest monthly UX meet-up with hundreds of user experience professionals 
attending each month, Why not become a partner and be seen by over 1000 UX attendees across 
networking events throughout the year. We are looking for three sponsors for 2016 to partner us in our 
events. 
Why Sponsor us? 
 Generate new leads 
 Build brand presence and raise profile in the UX community 
 Forge strategic partnerships and joint ventures
 Support the UX community 
 Network with industry people  
 Use us in your sales pitches to client’s, candidates and via your marketing info
What you will get as part of the package:
 Overall sponsorship of the event, with a particular focus on keynote sessions.
 Branding throughout pre-publicity across all communications channels (website and email 
communications), plus high visibility during the event in networking areas, event screens, 
agenda, attendee packs.
 Recognition at opening and closing of each event by presenter.
 Advertise your brand within the event using banners  
 Have your name included on our website and meet-up groups 
 Have you name printed on all our name badges 
 Post jobs on our UX Crunch website 
 Gain free sponsor tickets to all our events and offer them to your staff, candidates and clients

description:
The Salesforce community has over 800,000 developers worldwide and is rapidly growing. The community includes Heroku, force.com, data.com, site.com and all the platforms in the Salesforce ecosystem that support developers enjoy rapid, scalable application development.

This meetup group is part of that community, allowing developers to get together and discover great development practices, get to grips with new features, give feedback on APIs & the development experience.  By doing things together the potential for learning is far greater.

So, in the best traditions, this community is driven by its members for the benefit of its members.  So if you want to speak about projects you have worked on, want to host a meetup, tell people about blogs you have written, highlight your repositories on github, then let the community know.

The community organisers are here to help make things happen, its our members that shape what we do, so if you want to do something please let us know.

Thank you.

description:
Are you a lady? Do you code? Are you searching for a similar bunch of ladies to drink wine and discuss code with?

You’ve come to the right place. We meet monthly to hear talks from leaders in our field and hack whilst developing our code-fu in the process.

We use the following pillars of focus to make this user group insightful and engaging for you:

Professional development

This pillar covers deep focus on a variety topics to learn and discuss latest technology trends. These talks vary from specific platform focused sessions to more broad topics on best practices and guidelines. The format also varies from formal conference style to casual discussions and hands on katas.


Personal Development

From time to time the events will have inspirational talks and coaching sessions. This pillar focuses on building softer skills ranging from confidence building to leadership training.


Social engagement

This pillar is dedicated to social responsibility. As a community we are trying to collaborate with other local communities, charities and user groups, to help them achieve their goals.

So please join us if this sounds good to you. 

Also reach out if you are looking to sponsor, speak or are a similar community who we can collaborate/help in any way.

description:
Welcome to the html5 Codeshow! We are a group of hackers/developers/tech enthusiasts who are ecstatic about what the future of the web and mobile apps will bring. For years we've seen what the future might look like via sexy sci-fi films--well now the future is here and it's our turn to make that vision a reality! Join us in sharing our coding knowledge and let's develop ideas together over pizza and beer!

Are you working on a website, mobile web app, or designing a game? What are some of the challenges you’ve encountered that you will need to overcome in order to finish the project? Did you just have a breakthrough moment and would like to share it with the rest of the group? Maybe you’re looking for collaborators or just feedback from fellow hackers?

With a strong emphasis on best practices and problem-solving, this HTML5 meetup series aims at inviting developers to demo projects and interact with an audience of fellow programmers. The goal is to get your questions answered!  We will bring at least one expert speaker on board per session, but we want to keep this meetup really developer-centric.

Everyone is welcome to present at the next CodeShow as long as it's HTML5 related - we only ask you to keep it within 5-7 minutes and to let us know in advance if you wish to present (via personal message or in the comments)

This fun geek event will be as good as we all make it! Bring your hacks and your friends and join us for a night of html5 and its CSS3/javascript/flash/.etc friends!

Look forward to seeing you all there!

description:
District Health (formerly iBehave) is a meetup focused on the usage of technology as an enabler of behaviour change for positive health outcomes. Our mission is to:

1. Be a nucleus for the health tech and behaviour change community.

2. To embed rigour and scientific evidence in behaviour change technology.

 

Who should attend?

Entrepeneurs, developers, UX designers, gamification experts, clinicians, wellness practitioners, fitness trainers, behaviour change specialists… and really anyone who has an interest in this space and has something interesting to share.

What will you get out of it?

Connect with some great experts, mentors, potential co-founders, and unlock some great new business ideas and insights

description:
Restarters are people who like helping other learn how to fix broken electronics and electricals - anything with a battery or that plugs in - with a few exceptions for safety, like microwaves.

Restarters have diverse skills. Some help with basic electrical fixing involving changing fuses and plugs. Others deal with software issues on laptops and mobiles. What unites Restarters is the love of a repair challenge and their collaborative approach. Join us, make a difference, help empower people by teaching repair, and reduce e-waste.

The Restart Project promotes community self-repair events for Restarters called "Restart Parties" in greater Camden and Brixton. In other communities in London, other organisations host - we will indicate the hosts for events.

If you would like to reach out to more people by hosting your own Restart Party, write us at community@therestartproject.org

description:

Team Bitcoin

description:
Close your laptop lid and come down to the newest monthly Midlands' meetup: Derby Internet & IT Pros.

Head into the city and hook up with like minded members of Derby's thriving tech community. Share your latest tech finds, discuss your newest projects, make invaluable contacts or just fuel a heated debate about the iPhone 7.

Everyone's welcome, regardless of your background or experience: web designers; developers; systems engineers; networking pros; digital creatives; marketers or entrepreneurs. We're looking forward to welcoming you.

description:
Are you a technology startup based in and around South and South West London? Why not come along to one of our monthly(ish) meetings to discuss issues, meet like-minded individuals and talk tech - all over a few beverages.

We welcome anyone with an idea who needs help and of course anyone with the technology skills that startups need so badly.

We've been meeting semi regularly for a while already and have settled on a nice pub in Richmond as our normal venue (easy for mainline and tube) We've had people attend from some very well known startups as well as those who just have the seed of an idea. We've also had really informative speakers and discussions.

If this all sounds good to you then please join up and come along.

description:
Based in Huddersfield we are a group of like minded folk who are all involved with the digital industry in one way or another (web, print, design, programming, etc.).

We meet the last Wednesday of the month for a beer or two to share ideas, problems, solutions, tips & tricks or to just have a chat with someone else who understands what we are talking about without glazing over.

Meetings are a mix of either general socials, guest panels, speakers and nights out. Think of it as a geeky hen/stag do full of interesting people. Come down and say hi, interact and tell us about yourselves and what you do. We would love to see you :)

Students welcome (we are a university town after all), come meet/learn from those in the trenches and tell us some new stuff we might have missed.

description: This is a group for software Application Lifecycle Management (ALM) professionals in London, United Kingdom, who are particularly interested the Lean and Agile practices using Microsoft tools like Team Foundation Server (TFS), Microsoft Test Manager (MTM), Visual Studio and System Center. The user group meetings will cover all aspects of ALM including requirements gathering, performance metrics, all forms of testing, code management, configuration, build and deployment. The group will be of interest to business analysts, requirement engineers, developers, testers, project managers, build engineers and release managers. This group is not only about the ALM tools but also the methods, such as Scrum, Kanban, XP, CMMI, and practices, such as Continuous Delivery and BDD, that the ALM tools help facilitate.

description: ProductTank Manchester provides an opportunity for Product Managers in Manchester and the North to exchange ideas and experiences about Product Design, Development and Management, Business Modelling, Metrics, User Experience and all the other things that get us excited. description:
ProductTank Edinburgh (#ProductTankEdi) is a monthly meetup to exchange ideas and experiences about product management.

Our events feature guest talks on designing and building great web and mobile products, including topics such as design, agile processes, business models, using metrics, user experience, and more.

We also always build in time for networking, and a good old-fashioned chin-wag over a beverage or a slice of pizza!

Our events are public, but we ask everyone to provide a little information about themselves when they register so that we can build a good community.

ProductTank Edinburgh is part of the larger ProductTank network, which maintains a great blog—we encourage you to get engaged by commenting on or writing new posts for http://www.mindtheproduct.com.

ProductTank Edinburgh is sponsored by Skyscanner.

description: New technologies are constantly appearing and software development practices continue to adapt and evolve. Recently we have observed a new role emerging in the IT industry which has been labelled SDET or Software Developer in Test. This role has increasingly gained traction with the software industry and several employers have now started to recruit specifically for this role. The aim of the London SDET group is to bring together people who are interested in the SDET role to form a community where we can explore the role, share experiences and help provide the industry with greater clarity of what the role involves. We also hope to promote open communication, knowledge sharing and avenues for those wishing to become a SDET or for those wishing to hire a SDET as well as many ways to achieve excellence in the role.

description:
This newly relaunched group brings together people already running online businesses or those who are keen to start one to discuss ideas, challenges, successes and failures.

If you already run an online business or are about to start one then come along and tell everyone about it.

If you already run a traditional bricks and mortar business but want to take all of it or just part of it online then this group is also for you. You will almost certainly meet people who will be able to help.

description:
Ladies in Blogging is a networking group for women who blog or want to learn to blog, whether for professional or personal reasons. We are a supportive, non-competitive community focussed on helping and supporting each other to improve and grow as bloggers. 

The aim of the Ladies in Blogging group is to empower women to improve their skills and learn more about blogging and social media. We hold monthly networking events where you can other Ladies who blog and to listen to our speakers who will educate, entertain and inspire you. 

If you are not in London where we hold our networking events, we also have an online community at www.ladiesinblogging.com where you can network online instead of face to face. The website will be posting regular training for bloggers, SEO tips and regular podcasts. 

Our topics of discussion include: 

• 1. How to start blogging 

• 2. How to improve your writing 

• 3. How to improve your photography for your blog 

• 4. Increasing Blog Traffic

• 5. SEO strategies for Bloggers 

• 6. How to increase traction as a blogger 7. How to grow your audience 

• 8. Video Blogging 9. Mobile friendly Blog design 

• 10. Wordpress 

• 11. From blogger to published author 

• 12. Make money from your blog 

• 13. Working with Brands and PRs and more Come and join us at one of out networking events.

description:
There is more to the world than “functional cloud based self learning big data analytic enterprise visualisation dashboards”.

The only meetup focusing on data structures and algorithms, regardless of programming language or application domain.

No marketing speak. No handwaving.

Its easy to loose track of these fundamentals in day to day jobs and given how important they are for code quality and performance its worth giving them some dedicated time. Even if its just to prepare for you next job interview.

Examples of talks:

  • The Fast Fourier Transform, more useful than you think
  • Training deep neural networks: complexity analysis
  • The pumping lemma: Why should you care?
  • The multi-objective knapsack problem: strategies and applications
  • Leader election for collaborative drones
  • Variational inference in Bayesian Networks
  • Genetic Algorithms in Formula 1 design
  • ...

More examples and details here.

We have a healthy attendance with a good technical crowd. If you'd like to speak about your favourite data structure or algorithm, or if you just have a request for a talk, send an e-mail to the list or get in touch with the organiser.

Twitter account: @bigoldn
Hashtag: #bigoldn

description: "How to explain ØMQ? Some of us start by saying all the wonderful things it does. It's sockets on steroids. It's like mailboxes with routing. It's fast! And we're based in London.

description:
We hold regular meetups and micro-conferences, inviting a host of prominent professionals in the world of web to share their experiences and offer guidance to those new to the arena. With a philosophy of simplicity and conciseness, nearly all talks are shorter than 20 minutes and refreshingly “data-light”.

 

What do we talk about?

Subjects vary depending on the speaker, but each talk is focused towards learners and encourages interactivity. We attempt to cover all areas of importance to those new to working in web. Our aim is to whet the appetite for a rounded “Webucation” and direct learners towards the incredible materials found online so principles introduced here can be put into practice.

 

Who is the audience?

Anyone just stepping into the field of web design, web development, online marketing, content creation and so on will find tremendous benefit in attending our events. A full understanding of the fundamentals is essential for a successful career in web.

Of course, gaining this understanding is more difficult than it should be. With so many books, articles and videos available it’s hard to find good starting point. Our talks look to introduce the fundamentals gently, openly and without the barriers sometimes found elsewhere.

 

What we are NOT

Every night in London you can find a group of professionals gathered to digest a presentation on a particular technology. These meetups are fantastic and a credit to the community. Untangle the Web doesn’t contend with these events, we will rarely go into the analytical depths you may see elsewhere. We offer byte-sized, short-burst groundings in subjects and use our community to seek out resources for extending our understanding of the web.

description:
The North of England BlackBerry Developer Group has been founded by Interchange Group to help and assist developers (both new and established) with shared learning interests to network, get support and take BlackBerry development to the next level.

As an official RIM-sponsored BlackBerry Developer Group, these meetings will be a chance to learn about and share practical development tips and experience as well as to network with the local BlackBerry community.

Our goal is to build a knowledge sharing network for writing quality software on the BlackBerry platform - a place where you can turn for answers and advice. If you live or work in the North of England area, please join our community to stay abreast of the events, discussions, community and technology.

description:

description:
Health 2.0 Manchester is a meetup group focused on innovations in the delivery of healthcare and health related technology. This group is dedicated to creating a community around  digital healthcare in Manchester as part of the international Health 2.0 movement. This community  aims to share, discuss, showcase and develop ideas to improve patient care. If you are interested in the intersection of health care and information and communication technology, this is a community for you. Technology enthusiasts, developers, students, academics, physicians, nurses, pharmacists, patients, designers, social workers, NHS leaders, industry and entrepreneurs are welcome.

We will bring health and technology together to solve burning questions by :

  • connecting clinicians and entrepreneurs with developers
  • facilitating access to knowledge and markets by inviting speakers representing regulators, health care providers, industry

Come with an idea and find resources to make it happen. Come with a problem and find people who can help you to solve it. Come with a product and find clients and partners.

Health 2.0 has introduced over 500 technology companies to the world stage, hosted more than 9,000 attendees at conferences and code-a-thons, awarded over $2,823,000 in prizes through developer challenge program and inspired the formation of 54 new chapters in cities around the globe.

description:
The Brand Marketer Group is a friendly group and welcomes business owners, consultants, coaches and entrepreneurs. If you are one of among them, then come along to discover the strategies to build your brand and market your brand.

When we meet we discuss and share 4 important aspects of your business - 

•  Branding Your Solution

• Marketing Your Brand

• Converting Your Leads

• Generating More Profits

The Brand Marketer was co-founded by Chinmai Swamy and Naval Kumar. 

Chinmai has worked with some of the best world known brands and helped deliver value to their end clients. Brands like Suzuki, Bentley, Nokia, Symbian, Fujitsu, and Virgin are just some of them.

Naval on the other hand has worked on Digital Marketing Campaigns on both sides of the Atlantic and with brands such as CarsDirect, Vehix, Autos, Cars.com, lastminute.com, and Diesel to name a few...

Both of them are published authors, international speakers and business experts in their fields.

When you attend...you will be able to implement the strategies on both online and offline forms of marketing. Whether you are a single person running your business or a marketing manager working inside a business this event will benefit you towards getting attention from customers and converting leads into sales.

The purpose of the group is to share the latest strategies on sales, marketing, building websites, running social media campaigns, discuss case studies and also allow you to make useful connections, in a fun and informal atmosphere.

The usual format of events will be as follows:

    One or two short talks on small business marketing topics

    Followed by informal networking over drinks

    The chance to get feedback and information from the speakers and other attendees.

All are welcome at our regular, friendly events - so come along to learn, make connections, and share notes on websites, social media, blogging, SEO, pay-per-click, traffic generation strategies, WordPress, Twitter, Facebook, Google+, YouTube, Pinterest, LinkedIn, podcasting...

Questions? Please contact me and I'll be pleased to help.

Kind regards,

Chinmai Swamy and Naval Kumar

description:
This study group on SICP has been running every Jan-May since 2012, with a break in 2015.  This year, we are starting with a fast 3 session review on Ch1 and Ch2, before taking our time on Ch3, 4 and 5.

We meet fortnightly at Crowdmix's offices in Old Street.  Each session is structured so that you can drop in as you may, provided that you're up-to-date with the reading.  Please don't sweat having missed a session or two.

New for 2016, on our "off weeks" we are still meeting.  One group is working through the book Purely Functional Data Structures, while another group is working through the same material from the previous session to make sure its fully absorbed.

description:
We are a community of data scientists, technologists and analysts who work with data. This Meetup discusses the tools, methods and technologies used to analyse large scale data (big data), obtain predictive insight, and exploit business opportunities from data products.

We talk about topics like: big data analytics, distributed data analytics, Pig, Hive, data mining, machine learning, scalable data analytics, predictive analytics, statistical computing, applied statistics, R language, Python, NLP, large scale analytical paradigms, data science opportunities & challenges, data science learning & training...

No boring, theoretical presentations, but interesting, amusing, practical talks showcasing data science applications and data scientists' work along with practical demonstrations, interactions and sharing of ideas. Convivial get-togethers in St Aldates Tavern, talks and events around Oxford.

If you are interested in Data Science and you'd like to meet other data scientists who are passionate about data science, come and join us.

Twitter: datascienceoxon   |   Web: http://www.datascienceoxford.uk

description:
This group is a chance to meet fellow minded individuals, from people that has been doing DevOps for a long time to new starters!

We will try to cover anything and everything about DevOps including Automation, Orchestration, Containers, Virtualisation, Service Discovery, Continuous Integration and Continuous Delivery.

The objectives of the group are:

2. Help and foster the DevOps Community in London

description:
London’s Artificial Intelligence Futurists

This is a group for anyone interested in, or even wants to shape, the future. In particular we are focusing on the development and the impact of Artificial (General) Intelligence (AGI), Human Level Human Level Machine Intelligence (HLMI), Machine Learning, Robotics, Personal Robots, Intelligent Agents, Semantic Networks, theories about Human Intelligence, etc. The acceleration of technology provides more and more possibilities to achieve HLMI.

According to Ray Kurzweil “The Singularity is near” and it will bring radical changes to all of us. Taking part of the HLMI creating adventure actively and discussing its impact on us makes it an exciting development and the major aim of this group. What’s your view? How do you think HLMI could be achieved? Are we entering into a new brilliant age? What does HLMI means in comparison to human intelligence? Do you think of a “Human 2.0” or “Human+”? Are you keen to create HLMI? Should principle rules for AGI been established?

Anybody is welcome to this group – HLMI/AGI needs anthropology, philosophy, mathematics, physics, psychology, computer science, brilliant programmers, and so on – to shape HLMI and discuss its impact everyone is welcome. The future belongs to us all!

Join the debate, share your opinion and meet interesting new people.

 

Upcoming topics

Cutting through the complexity and simplify it is in particular import in an AI-context. To do so, here a couple of upcoming topics:

  1. We will question the doctrine of the human uniqueness in order to find basic repeating patterns. To do so will not be a huge issue. A lot of research is available that shows us what we need to know for understanding the way a HLMI could look like.
  2. Once we’ve got an understanding of the basic human patterns we are going to questioning the human intelligence. How could human intelligence be defined? What is the most promising intelligence frame work which could be used for HLMI? To answer these questions latest research results are very helpful. Just a glance at Jeff Hawkings OnIntelligence or Ray Kurzweils ”How to create a mind” shows us we will be able to define a framework for HLMI.
  3. When we have a useful intelligence framework we will go further to synthesize it to the HLMI basic requirements.
  4. Based on the HLMI we will be able to discuss the impact of a HLMI -System.

You like to discuss a specific topic at the meetup? Please let us know it!

 

Support London’s Artificial Intelligence Futurists

 

If you join the debate please consider supporting us with a donation.

Please help to cover us:

  •  
    • cost of room hire
    • cost of this Meetup website
    • other administration expenses.

Each donation helps. You can donate easy and safe via PayPal:

|| Donate £ 5 || Donate £ 10 || Donate £25 || Your choice of donation ||

Thank you very much for your help

Robert M Wenzel

description:
A warm welcome to Big Data / Data Science / Data Analytics Jobs!

With Data growing at such an exponential rate, organisations are flocking to find solutions of how to manage their Critical Data. This has created a new breed of expertise that is in somewhat short supply.

This group aims to bring together a community with a common interest in analysing, understanding and monetising Big Data, create opportunities for those who are able to do so and solve a few problems for Organisations’ who are not.

We are interested in hearing about the latest technological trends and breakthroughs, war stories and common pain points currently faced by clients but more importantly current projects that require resource solutions.

From time to time we will also host an event with food & drink and one or 2 guest speakers to boot.

We hope you enjoy your stay!

description:

• Connecting people so that they can collaborate & work together in the future

description:

Theses communities are hosting local meetups and hackathons that have stirred passionate developers and entrepreneurs to action creating apps and solutions across diverse sectors spanning transportation, energy, waste, water, and agriculture.

Cleanweb is just getting started in Scotland. We're keen to meet entrepreneurs, developers, designers, makers, activists, and anyone interested in sustainability. If you're interested in speaking at one of our events please get in touch with the organisers.

More about Cleanweb can be found on:

  • Cleanweb UK
  • Cleanweb Scotland on Twitter
  • Cleanweb Scotland on Facebook
  • Cleanweb Global

description:
There’s a stack of social media gurus out there telling you why you need to use social media in your business. What we’re offering is a little different.

Using years of experience of producing web content and social media campaigns for small businesses and household names like AOL, Yahoo!, the BBC, ITV, Toshiba, Magic FM, Paul Smith and Pizza Hut, Sue Keogh and Christine Cawthornes use all their editorial expertise to show you how to write for social media.

PLEASE NOTE!

After a series of sellout workshops at Google Campus and other venues, we're not running any more sessions under the Sweet Retweets name; please look us up at our respective websites: www.crocstar.com and www.sookio.com.

You may also be interested in joining another group run by Sue, Sookio Masterclasses: Straight-talking social media: http://www.meetup.com/Sookio-Masterclasses/

description:
A free meet-up for UX and UX-curious people, on the second Tuesday of every month in Bristol. We're a group for open discussion on all User Experience/Usability, from software to web design to mobile apps. We usually meet for a chat, networking, general conversation, and  we have a UX design related slide presentation/talk/workshop with time for questions etc. Why not come along, and discuss or give a slide presentation on your own projects or usability interests?

Anyone can give a presentation/workshop (regardless of their background), post and view Usability/UX related information - we're really keen on open discussion for all, to share experience and learn. We ask what talk topics are of interest so these can be included in future monthly talks. 

We're also on Linked-in as a group so people can share info about related available work. Dave Jones looks after us on Linked-in, so please contact him if you have any queries re that.

Jobs/recruitment etc:  If you have a job role to post, please use our Linked-in page. Posting jobs on the SWUX pages is not encouraged, not least because of the way the comment system works, most people won't see it. If you want us to tweet jobs, we will, if it is for direct hire. No agencies please.

Twitter: https://twitter.com/SW_UX

Web: http://www.swux.org.uk

description:
The world is increasingly full of change, complexity and uncertainty.

It's time for a new mentality and a rethink of our organisations. We can unleash the potential of everyone in the workplace.

It's time for less control, more collaboration. Fewer assumptions, more rapid feedback. More simplicity.

It's time for less management, more leadership. Less meetings, more conversations. Less bonuses, more fulfilment. Less "fully utilised resources", more slack to foster innovation.

Companies with a positive purpose have the advantage. The obsession with share prices and short-term profit is an obstacle to sustainable success.

We don't have all the answers. We will learn together. This is just the start - it's Columbus standing on the shores of the New World. Welcome to the Stoos Network.

description:
Come Together For Health™

Improving access to affordable healthcare by promoting innovative technologies that transform healthcare.

Health Technology Forum (HTF) is a platform for people worldwide who have a common interest in making healthcare better, more accessible and affordable. Our international network of technology and healthcare entrepreneurs, developers, regulators, and providers are advancing the pace of healthcare innovation by engaging in exciting and productive dialogue between experts in healthcare.

Worldwide interconnections are critical as we think global and act local. The advent of PHRs, social network, open platforms, smart phone, personalized medicine, compliance, interoperability, and policies are creating new opportunities for everyone to engage in a dialog to improve care everywhere.

At our local meetups we discuss real-life technology use-cases from hospitals, doctor offices, medical billing, insurance, remote monitoring, pharmaceuticals, health-and-wellness, and various patient-care services. Subject matter experts, users, entrepreneurs, regulators, and providers will address each other's needs and solutions. The objective is to connect entrepreneurs with professionals who are addressing these real-life problems that exist in the healthcare ecosystem. We will review how low-cost, scalable, deployable systems can meet or exceeds the needs of 21st century care-giving for everyone.

To learn more, please visit our website: www.healthtechnologyforum.com

description:
What is the 'Internet of Things' and how do Small Manufacturing businesses work with it?

Our informal 'Show and Tell' Meetup will feature short talks from those innovating with IoT applicable technologies in the Manufacturing Sector. The aim is to build a community of like-minded organisations willing to collaborate, explore and innovate with IoT products, services and applications.

Come and meet, discuss, explore and be inspired.

The WMG SME Group is a dynamic team based at the University of Warwick, pioneering university support for innovation in small and medium sized businesses. We accelerate productivity and growth in SMEs by applying research-led tools and techniques, building sustainable and collaborative relationships.

We provide workshops and technology demonstrations, access to cutting edge manufacturing equipment, and customised company projects. We also offer technology focused networking events and opportunities for joint research. Funded by Innovate UK, our support is available to SMEs in the manufacturing sector.

Support Themes: Smart Factories, Smart Products, Low Volume Manufacturing, Materials Testing, Customer Insights, and New Business Models

Contact Us

Via Twitter: @WMGSME or wmgsme@warwick.ac.uk

Events are hosted in the International Institute for Product and Service Innovation (IIPSI) at the University of Warwick, Coventry CV4 7AL.

IIPSI is Part-funded and supported by the European Regional Development Fund (ERDF).

The terms and conditions for attending our meetings can be found at:

description:
Head over to our new site, especially for the Drupal Show and Tell events, to see videos of previous talks: http://www.drupalshowandtell.com

We're holding monthly Drupal "Show and Tell" evenings at London South Bank University. Each month we'll be calling on people to present a short Drupal related technical talk to the rest of the group.

Your talk could be on anything from a neat solution you've discovered for a tricky problem to your latest favourite feature of Drupal 8. We aim to have a few talks that last around 15 minutes each (with some extra time for questions and discussion).

You don't have to be a Drupal guru to submit a talk! We're looking for a diverse mix of talks and this is a relaxed atmosphere where people who've never done a Drupal presentation before should feel at home.

The very kind people at London Southbank University have donated a great space for one evening per month. It's the 8th floor of their conference building and has space for about 40 with great views over London.

Tea, coffee and sandwiches will be provided and after the session we'll have a pint or two in the pub across the road, so please join us for that too.

description:
To join this forum please just answer two questions below and send us your profile picture.

This social group is for TV, online and mobile media professionals located in the UK and Ireland.

Vizrt UK is a team committed to helping fellow TV and digital platform professionals like you to enhance your brand with real-time graphics, to get the most out of your digital media assets and to publish integrated digital online and mobile content in the most attractive and cost-efficient way.

If you would like to come to a fun venue where you can meet up regularly with like-minded professionals and with us, we would like to invite you to join our Vizrt Forum.

This informal forum will give you a chance to talk to fellow super-users from your industry, share ideas, solve problems, learn about new custom development, interactivity, 3rd Party integrations and control applications and talk to members of Vizrt’s marketing, senior management or R&D team about our products, services and roadmap. This is your chance to be heard.

We aim to host informal get-togethers in a central London location. At each meet-up, a guest speaker will make a short presentation about a specific technology of interest or share a clever way our products have been used. Sometimes we might demo a new unreleased software product, so you will know what we have been working on and can tell us what you think of it. After that, we hope our members will get into the spirit and start talking to one another - and us - over a pint or two.

Our aim is to stimulate new ideas and relationships by providing a way for you to meet similar users to yourself and to hear from you what we are doing right, what new areas we should be looking at and what needs to change.

We plan to organise a meet-up every 4-6 weeks with topics for future events suggested by you, as the group grows.

You should definitely join the Vizrt Forum if you:

- are a 3D graphics designer, especially for live TV events and online publishing

- are a journalist, editor or producer who is interested in “Big Data” for TV, online or mobile

- are passionate about IP or mobile newsgathering and delivery

- are a programmer or support engineer for a digital media platform

- want to share ideas with others who use the same production, archive and creative tools that you do.

- want to expand your knowledge of media asset management and online content management

- have an interest in real-time 3D graphics, 3D maps and live, data-driven graphics

- are curious about Virtual and Augmented Reality for news, sports and entertainment

- want to create top-quality 3D sports analyses using the latest interactive tools

We hope you will send us your application so we can invite you to our first meet-up. Look out for our email with details and we hope there will be many more to come.


Maja, Joanna and the Vizrt UK team

description:
Leeds JS is a user group in that meets in Leeds on the last Wednesday of every month. Join us for free food, a beer, prizes and to meet a great bunch of people.

The goal of this user group is to form a community for Javascript in Leeds. Most technical companies now have to use javascript in some way and the demand is growing with every new framework and NodeJS release. We want to be a place were any developer can come for advice, to show off what they're working on or to just talk about the news (and drama) in the wider Javascript community.

This user group is for the community! If you ever want to pitch in or have an idea just get in touch via twitter https://twitter.com/leedsjs

Things to expect from this meet up:

  • Interactive demos for attendees - make sure to charge your smartphone!
  • Noobs, Intermediates, Experts, Gurus...everyone is welcome.
  • Splendid prizes up for grabs each meet.
  • A say in the direction of the group and what talks we put on.
  • Conference discounts available.

Good stuff, we hope to see you at the next meet =)

We also now have a website and blog running on the NodeJS blogging engine Ghost. Check it out at leedsjs.com

Please note the group is intended for developers looking to expand their knowledge in a recruiter free zone only so whilst interest from recruitment consultants is nice we have a no recruiters policy.

description:
ICT4E is a collaborative learning platform linking NGOs to the growing networked age of humanitarian assistance.

Composed of LinkedIn Discussions, Causal Meet-ups and Presentations, the group is a fun, open space that brings together a cross-section of like minded people who want to transform the way aid agencies use information technology in emergencies.

ICT4E puts special emphasis on the on the needs of practitioners and “how” these can be met in simple, practical ways.

It’s open to anyone from aid workers to enthusiasts looking to mobilize practical action between the NGO, Private & Academic sectors.

We’re actively looking to hook up to wider initiatives (Communication 4 Development; ICT4D; Crisis Mappers; The Standby Volunteer Task; Apps4Good; Hack 4 Humanity; Ushahidi etc).

Feel free to sign up, ask questions and share ideas. Moreover, come join the global LinkedIn discussion http://www.linkedin.com/groups/ICT4E-Information-Communication-Technology-Emergencies-4951824?home=&gid=4951824&trk=anet_ug_hm.

Looking forward to meeting you online or at the next ICT4E MeetUp!

Cheers,

Alesh

description: So what is a Drupal co-working day? Essentially, it's a chance for Drupal professionals to work alongside each other for the day. Drupal co-working days take place all over the world each month. It's free, and as Third Door will be celebrating their 3rd Birthday, they'll be Cake (as well as the usual pastries and supply of tea and coffee) Other Drupal folks would be there to talk to, collaborate, advise (and likewise for the attendee). An entire section of the space (either a full desk or the meeting room) will be dedicated for Drupal professionals See http://groups.drupal.org/node/195983 for the Drupal Coworking Friday FAQ and the Coworking group at http://groups.drupal.org/coworking for general information about coworking. Just bring your laptop, your business cards or whatever else you need. You don't have to be from South-West London to come join us! You don't even have to be from London! Or anywhere! What's important is that you know (some) Drupal and want to work with other professionals in a really nice co-working space for a day.

description:

description:

description:
DNAdigest is a charity created to shake up genomics research: loads of DNA sequencing data is being generated, but not enough data is being shared between researchers, a fact which is a huge barrier for the advancement medical research. With our not-for-profit organisation DNAdigest we are promoting and enabling tools and mechanisms that facilitate efficient and secure data access for research.

The biggest challenge for enabling data sharing is not the implementation of the solution, but to engage all stakeholders to join in the effort to develop the solutions and share data. We need to make researchers realise that data sharing is worth the effort, and we need to inform patients that their data is currently not put to optimal use, so that they may demand changes in the way institutions handle their data.

We need your help in making this happen:

- how can we best promote our cause?

- how can we raise funding for implementing solutions?

- how can we reach out and inform patient groups?

If you think you can help us or support us in any way, with your advice, your insight or your time, join our group to get involved in the discussion.

 

Kind regards,

-Fiona-

CEO and founder DNAdigest.org

description:
Free workshop which teaches delegates how to build their own WordPress website.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UOCxAZ3lYR4

The workshop consists of two parts:

Between 10.00-12.00 there will be a presentation that covers the basics of building a website and explains key terms such as domain, web hosting, WordPress, themes, plugins, widgets, pages, posts, etc. This section of the course is free for anyone to attend.

From 12.00-18.00 there will be a hands-on course that shows delegates, in a step-by-step fashion, how to build a WordPress website. This part of the workshop is completely free for delegates who don’t have web hosting to attend.

See what previous attendees have to say:

Delegates who already have web hosting are required to £50 to attend this section of the course. There will also be two guest speakers presenting original material during this time.

Delegates must:

·  Must bring your own laptop.

·  Be prepared to learn in a large group (40-50).

Throughout the course, WordPress nannies/assistants will be available to provide support. 

Complete the three steps below to attend: 

1. RSVP on this Meetup group

2. Complete the sign-up form

3. Watch the video tutorial below and set up a domain, hosting, and WordPress:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?feature=player_embedded&v=VMrDRZtpYPQ

How to start a WordPress blog

This course will show you how to create your very own website using WordPress, the most famous content management system in the world.

More testimonials from previous attendees:

https://www.facebook.com/luckywebs.co.uk/reviews

description:
WordPress is the world's #1 CMS and one of it's greatest strengths is its huge user community.  WPUGL brings together London's community of WordPress users to share knowledge, tips, ideas and inspiration, helping each other get the most out of WordPress.


We will be running regular, FREE events in central London with an informal atmosphere, encouraging everyone to share their knowledge and learn from others.


Each event will focus on a specific aspect of WordPress, chosen by you, the community.  Meetups will include hands on 'peer to peer' workshops, advice from WordPress professionals and the chance to network with other WordPress users.


This meetup group is specifically for people who use WordPress in their business, jobs or personal projects and want a supportive local community to help them achieve their goals.  WPUGL is not a developer meetup but we strongly encourage developers and industry professionals to volunteer at events and support the user community.

description:
Through Agile:MK, we invite everyone to help drive the adoption and improvement of Agile methodologies in Milton Keynes and the surrounding area. We do this through sharing experiences, talking with experts within areas of interest, and creating a space for Agile professionals to network and share their successes and challenges with adopting and practicing Agile. 

Through doing this we want to raise the standards of professional working life for the Agile community in our area.

For news about Agile in Milton Keynes our events and other updates, check out our website at agilemk.org and follow us on twitter: @AgileMK.

description: This is a group for any developers interested in creating virtual environments and telepresense games and applications building on the latest generation of virtual reality technology led by the launch of the Oculus Rift head-mounted display. The event will be hosted by Inition at our Shoreditch Demo Studios, with beers across the road at the Horse and Groom pub afterwards. Inition have a wide range of VR hardware, some of which will be made available at the Meetup. We're really excited that VR is finally coming-of-age, opening up unprecedented opportunities to create mind-blowing experiences and welcome like-minded creatives and developers to join us!

description:
What is Couchbase?

Couchbase is the company behind Couchbase open source project, a vibrant community of developers and users of Couchbase document-oriented database technology. 

Couchbase Server is a packaged version of Couchbase technology that’s available in Community and Enterprise Editions. Couchbase is known for easy scalability, consistent high performance, 24x365 availability, and a flexible data model. 

Companies like AOL, Cisco, Concur, LinkedIn, Orbitz, Salesforce.com, Shuffle Master, Zynga and hundreds of others around the world use Couchbase Server for their interactive web and mobile applications.

Sign up to our Couchbase Developer Newsletter

description:
Silicon Canal's mission is to create a world class tech eco-system across Greater Birmingham. We are connecting, promoting & supporting tech & digital businesses from freelancers, startups through to multinationals. Together we can make Greater Birmingham a beacon for tech & digital companies.

Silicon Valley has inspired a number of tech hubs across the globe. You’ve got Silicon Alley (New York), Silicon Hills (Texas) and closer to home Silicon Roundabout and Silicon Fen. 

And now joining them: Silicon Canal. 

This meetup is a very informal social meetup, just about getting a load of like-minded people involved with tech, tech startups & digital stuff in Birmingham together. No agenda, just a good time & the chance to catch up with friends/colleagues/some new faces. We meet on the first Thursday of the month from 6:30pm.

To keep informed of other great tech events going on sign up to the silicon canal mailing list - Silicon Canal

description:
Join us at the GeoDev meetup, run by Esri UK!

The GeoDev meetup is an open, friendly, technical gathering for developers to discuss geospatial technologies, complementary third-party tools and development platforms that are supported by Esri. At the meetup you can:

•             Demonstrate your application/framework.

•             Present an interesting concept or idea.

•             Share your experiences.

•             Connect with other developers.

We welcome presentations and conversations around Esri's APIs, SDKs and tools: from web development in JavaScript & REST, to mobile development on iOS, Android and Windows Phone, to automating tasks with Python.

Developers of all levels of expertise are welcome, from seasoned software application developers to those new to geospatial development, we aim to be inclusive.To see what is possible with Esri's APIs and SDKs you can check out http://developers.arcgis.com to get a deeper understanding.

Be sure to bring your business card and share your ideas with your peers.  Contact geodev@esriuk.com if you're interested in doing a lighting talk about a project or idea you have.

Because we care about our community and want to foster a positive atmosphere at our events, attendees are expected to follow a code of conduct whilst participating at our meetups which can be seen at: http://confcodeofconduct.com . Please take a quick moment to read this page. 

Feel free to follow us on Twitter:  

• http://www.twitter.com/EsriUKGeoDev

• http://www.twitter.com/JamesLMilner

description:
London GlassFish & Java EE User Group (GUG) is here to distribute GlassFish related knowledge and provide a meeting place for GlassFish users to get information, share resources and solutions, increase networking, expand GlassFish Technology expertise, and above all - drink beer, eat pizza and have fun.

As a user group we encourage people to volunteer to talk about their experiences with any GlassFish Community project. We aim to create the GlassFish community and to share real world experiences with other members of the community.

About GlassFish

GlassFish is a robust, production quality, open source, Java EE compatible application server that is free for development, deployment, and redistribution.

GlassFish is the reference implementations for Java EE 6 (3.x)  and Java EE 7 (4.x) and is the community focus for building and contributing to the latest Java EE specifications. GlassFish is always at the cutting edge of Java EE and provides rapid support for emerging Java EE standards. However GlassFish is still suitable for large scale production Java EE applications.

To find out more about GlassFish visit https://glassfish.java.net/index.html and https://blogs.oracle.com/theaquarium/

description:
The Analytics Network is a special interest group of the professional body, The Operational Research Society. For those with an interest in analytics, in topics such as data science, optimisation, visualisation, Big Data, Regression, Data Mining, Predictive modelling or forecasting, the Analytics Network is intended to be your home within the Operational Research Society (The O.R. Society).

The O.R. Society was established over 75yrs ago, to promote the application of scientific methods to data, to enable decision-making and advice-giving. The O.R. Society has always provided a professional home for those working in both O.R., Analytics and Data Science; this group aims to bring together resources, news, views and information for just that purpose.

description:
Thanks for stopping by.

This is the Bristol & South West MySQL meetup page. We started the group so we can get together and discuss MySQL and the surrounding technologies. Bristol and Bath are thriving places for tech companies and being that MySQL remains the most popular Open Source DBMS on the planet it's clear that there will be a few people in the area with MySQL to chaperone.

The aim of this group is to attract MySQL Dev and DBAs and we really want to appeal to the Rubists, Perl, Python, PHP, Linux Sys Admin users in the extended area.

There is no single commitment to venue so we can be moved from place to place depending on the need and we will regularly have someone talking on a topic which will be interesting to anyone using MySQL in their daily tasks.
