description:
"This is huge huge news, the future of all Apple development." - John Gruber, 2nd June 2014


WELCOME TO SWIFT LONDON 

We're all beginners again, let's begin together.


WHO WE ARE

On 2nd June 2014, in a darkened hall in Moscone West, a new programming language was born. We followed three days after. Welcome to Swift London! 

First and foremost we are a collaborative community, for developers of all abilities and backgrounds, who want to learn about Swift. We are run by enthusiasts, we're independent, and we're not-for-profit.

Everyone is welcome!


WHAT WE DO

We hold a monthly Talks night, socials, and practical Hands On sessions as often as we can. We've been known to arrange workshops too. If you want to come along and discuss ideas, you'd be very welcome.

We learn together, we support each other, and we're growing something special.  


COLLABORATION

If you'd like to speak, arrange an evening, or host Swift London, we're always looking for interesting topics and venues. If you're interested in collaborating we'd be very happy to hear from you.

Twitter @SwiftLDN  
Email hello@swiftldn.co
Meetup messages


 Before attending, please read our CODE OF CONDUCT and INCLUSIVITY page.

description:
¿Qué es el TapasValley? 

TapasValley es un grupo de networking pensado tanto para los profesionales con experiencia en el sector de tecnologías e internet como para personas interesadas en entrar en este sector. Al mismo tiempo, las profesiones de sus asistentes será variada, así que tanto si eres desarrolador, diseñador, profesional de Márketing o desempeñas otra profesión en el sector, vente a tomar algo con nosotros :-) 

¿Quién lo organiza? 

TapasValley es un evento no afiliado a organización alguna. TapasValley fue fundado por Ivan Gadeschi (Badoo.com, YPlan…) y Javier Galán (TripAdvisor.com, Alibaba.com, CircleMe…) con el propósito de convertirlo en un evento que pueda ser de ayuda para todos los profesionales españoles que trabajan en el sector de tecnologíe e internet en Londres.


Tras 8 meses de geniales TapasValleys, finalmente hemos creado un grupo en meetup.com. Podéis encontrarnos también en:

Twitter: http://www.twitter.com/tapasvalley 
Facebook:http://www.facebook.com/tapasvalley  
Linkedin: https://www.linkedin.com/groups/Tapas-Valle... 
Nuestra web http://www.tapasvalley.com

description:

description:
This is a sub-group of the OMN London digital marketing community focusing specifically on all areas of personal branding and its growing importance to career making in the future of work.

Page one of Google, for your name is becoming a battleground where reputations are made and lost. 

It's the first place employers look after your CV. 

The careers of doctors, lawyers, accountants and other professional services professionals are being destroyed through negative reviews and malicious blog posts.

It's vital that everyone understands the simple steps they need to take to protect themselves from attacks, and also how they can own and leverage this personal media space to enhance their reputations and build success.  

It takes 20 years to build a reputation and five minutes to ruin it. If you think about that, you'll do things differently.

- Warren Buffet

It takes many good deeds to build a good reputation, and only one bad one to lose it.

- Benjamin Franklin

description:
Love the power of a hand-drawn image?

Are you a visual thinker but consider yourself rubbish at drawing? Are you doodling in meetings and want to improve your range of images? Are you an experienced graphic recorder who wants some focused time to try out some new techniques?  Anyone who loves the power of hand-drawn images and text is welcome, regardless of ability.

Want to practice your skills in a friendly, focused group?

We’re a community of practice. We learn by doing. We iterate to improve. There are no rules about what’s good or bad. If you come, you can practice in a friendly, fun and focused place. There’s a structured agenda: we warm up, we practice the basics and then we sketchnote an interesting talk from YouTube.  We talk about what we learned and if we want to, we can share our work and get input from others like us.

What to expect

Expect to be challenged and inspired, supported and motivated. Expect to have fun and be surprised by how much you can improve with a couple of regular hours of practice.

Some useful links to introduce Sketchnoting

 - An intro to visual note taking by Claudine Delphine

- An intro to Mike Rohde's sketchnoting approach (watch the Pecha Kucha video)

- An intro to graphic recording by Tanya Gadsby

-An example of sketchnoting a conference, on paper and with animation, by Matthew Magain

description: TLDR; Love data? Come to The Hub and meet others with the same passion! Hello!, We're starting a regular meetup in Jersey for anyone interested in all things related to data science. Perhaps you run a business and have tons of sales data and wish to spot trends in customer purchases? Or perhaps you run a website and you want to understand how visitors browse your content. Or you are a journalist who wants to publicise issues buried deep in mountains of government data. Or work in a myriad of other areas where knowledge, business intelligence, decision support or forecasting rest on the ability to visualise, model and reason about large data sets. If you do, and like us you have a passion for using the latest technology to solve these problems then come and meet us! We plan to meet regularly to discuss the latest issues that affect our work, share tips and demo the latest tools. By networking and sharing ideas and know-how we hope to build a community here on Jersey to support and benefit us all. We will be having our inaugural meeting on Monday the 30th of June at the The Hub, Digital Jersey's exciting new co-working space. This is all new and we're just booting up. Based on interest we'll start to decide the future shape of this group at that first meetup. Things that we’d like to talk about at the first event: * Tools and data sources for collecting data * Favourite analysis and visualisation tools * Notable projects - either something of your own or something from the web that makes you go ‘Wow!' We hope to see you there, in the meantime have fun! Paul & Matt

description:
Mission:

Women Who Code is a global nonprofit organization dedicated to inspiring women to excel in technology careers by creating a global, connected community of women in technology. The organization tripled in 2013 and has grown to be one of the largest communities of women engineers in the world.

Empowerment:

Women Who code is a professional community for women in tech. We provide an avenue for women to pursue a career in technology, help them gain new skills and hone existing skills for professional advancement, and foster environments where networking and mentorship are valued.

Key Initiatives:

Free technical study groups

Events featuring influential tech industry experts and investors

Hack events

Career and leadership development

Current and aspiring coders are welcome. 

Bring your laptop and a friend! 

Support Women Who Code:

Donating to Women Who Code, Inc. (#46-4218859) directly impacts our ability to efficiently run this growing organization, helps us produce new programs that will increase our reach, and enables us to expand into new cities around the world ensuring that women and girls everywhere have the opportunity to pursue a career in technology.

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, sexual orientation, ability, physical appearance, body size, race, ethnicity, age, religion, or socioeconomic status. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. Our Code of Conduct applies to all events run by Women Who Code, Inc. If you would like to report an incident or contact our leadership team, please submit an incident report form.

WomenWhoCode.com

Twitter | Facebook

bristol@womenwhocode.com

WomenWhoCode.com

description:
This is a group for programmers who wish to deepen their knowledge of programming. We're looking to dig in depth into the classic books of our field, such as Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs (SICP), Compilers: Principles, Techniques, and Tools (The dragon book), Lisp In Small Pieces, The Elements of Computing Systems (TECS) or Purely Functional Data Structures. And fundamental topics to the craft of programming, such as Compilers, Algorithms, Datastructures or Programming languages.

We meet regularly to study together and help each other understand programming in a relaxed atmosphere. We run series on given topics, usually following the chapters of a book.

We welcome all members who wish to learn more about the craft of programming, irrespective of their background, whether novice or experts. 

You can find out about our current and planned topics of study on Trello.

We look forward to meeting you at the next study session :)

Recruiter policy

Recruiters beware! Using this group as a forum for recruitment will not be tolerated as it puts our sponsorship and the quality of our events at risk. This group is for programmers to practice their craft. Off topic posts or messages will be blocked and members may be removed for repeated violation. 

You are welcome to any of our event, but only to learn.

If your company instead wishes to engage with members in a meaningful way, we would be happy to discuss possible sponsorships. Send a meetup message to the organisers to discuss this further.

description:
This is a meet up group for women based in or around Edinburgh, involved or interested in python programming. All levels are welcome, from professional programmers to those completely new to programming of any sort! We plan to have informal monthly meetups, as well as occasional talks and other one-off events. 

PyLadies is an international mentorship group with a focus on helping more women become active participants and leaders in the Python open-source community. Our mission is to promote, educate and advance a diverse Python community through outreach, education, conferences, events and social gatherings. PyLadies also aims to provide a friendly support network for women and a bridge to the larger Python world. Anyone with an interest in Python is encouraged to participate! Follow us on Twitter @PyLadiesEdin.

description:
At our monthly Drupal meetups we get together to talk, share knowledge and exchange ideas. Introductions, getting to know how we're using Drupal and supporting eachother to increase our skills.

Also seeing what people's needs are and planning future events to fit in with those needs along with some social events of course!

General Drupal Q&A for anyone attending (beginner through to advanced)

Bringing our problems (and possibly laptops too!) to the table and see if we can come up with solutions together

Spreading awareness of any upcoming events of interest and mentioning interesting opportunities

Update on progress of the group aims and any other general business

The event is hosted by Imagine Creativity

description:
Geek Girls Carrots is a community of women who love new technologies. It is a community for us
to participate and act on our passions. Among us there are programmers, graphic designers, project managers, planners, system architects, developers, IT managers, computer science students, analysts, social media specialists, girls with startup ideas and many more. Sometimes, we are joined by journalists who want inspiration for articles about local talent and new technologies.
The mission of our community is to promote women in IT and help to educate them and inspire their pursuits. We also want to motivate women to run their own projects and establish new technology related companies.
At our meetings we discuss topics related to the new technologies and careers in the field. We have no theme, focusing primarily on the selection of insuring and interesting speakers.
Currently Geek Girls Carrots operated in 14 cities in Poland, 1 in Germany, 1 in the USA  2 in Luxembourg and 1 in London.

description:
Apache Mesos simplifies the development and operation of resource efficient distributed applications. According to Chris Fry, SVP of Engineering at Twitter Mesos is one of the primary keys to their data centre efficiency. 


Mesos can already run a wide range of existing distributed technologies including, Hadoop, Spark and Storm. In addition there is a growing ecosystem of frameworks built just for Mesos such as Chronos created by aribnb as distributed cron replacement and Marathon for running longer running applications.

description:
The One-stop shop for SMEs and Start-ups!

We bring people in the Silicon Roundabout together to discuss, share, pitch and network. 

In London’s competitive investment climate, entrepreneurs often lack the business connections and brand awareness to get the attention of potential funders, and at the same time many investors don't have a pipeline into early-stage technology and Internet companies.

Tech City coffee provides a unique funnel for innovators to interact with a wide range of investors, present their plans, receive expert feedback, bring in strong leadership, and pave the way for them to receive angel and institutional funding. 



Find below the 10 key Business modules that all starts ups founders should know about:


Core modules for Business development and Management:

1. Project management

incl. outsourcing

2. Product development

  incl. Lean start up, MVP, Ux/UI, graphics design

3. Managing teams

incl. hiring, training

4. Finance

Incl. Financial management and modelling, accounting

5. Legal

  incl. Employment law, IP

6. Operations

incl. admin, logistice, procedure/process/policy

7.  Marketing and Sales

  Incl. Growth hacking, CRM, BI

8. Scaling strategy

  Incl. Growth

9. Fund raising

  incl. Investment, SEIS/EIS

 Funding: what do I need to know to negotiate with investors

Business Plan Writing: what is most important for investors

10. Product – Market fit

incl. Testing, Market research, Pivot






“Investment ready”

Requirements, to be in the top 1 %:

1. 10 slide pitch deck,

2. Pitching practice, 

   Practice makes perfect. 

   There is no substitute for practice.

3. Business plan


Pitch deck and pitching to Investor

All companies that pitch at the event will use the same pitch deck.

If your company would like to pitch to the investors, then request the 
“10 slide pitch deck – 5 min pitch” template.

First, you will have to send me all 7 items/information about your company:

1.description, 2. age, 3. stage, 4. team, 5. investments, 6. Traction, 7. Website.


Investor meeting conduct

You will get to meet with many investors in this meetup group.  Follow this code:

1. Primarily, research and read the Investors website, in particular their portfolio.  2. Investigate and check if the VC is a relevant fit for you and your company.  3. Be prepared to spend a percentage of your time on a regular basis to get investment.  4.  There are no short/quick fixes to the investment process.  5.  You will need to meet with several investors over a long period of time.  6.  Do not form a queue in order to talk to a VC, during the networking session.  7. Do not cold approach investors.  It is better to get to know them by a warm introduction from a person within their network



Four stages of growth and Investment


Tech investors make Tech investment based on the Tech Milestones that you achieve

These are guidelines for you to follow, when looking  for investors/investment:

Stage 1: Idea

Investment size – up to £ 50 k

Risk to investor - Extremely high

Milestones - You have a good idea and are putting together a team. 

You will need to form a UK based company.

Stage 2: Seed stage

Investment size – up to £ 150 k (SEIS)

Risk to investor - High

Milestones - You product has been successfully tested and you are about to launch.

                       You also have a great team.

You will need to register for "HMRC: SEIS Advanced assurance"


Stage 3: Revenue

Investment size – up to £ 250 k

Risk to investor - Medium

Milestones - Your company has recurring UK revenues and significant traction.

Both the quality and the quantity of the revenue/traction is important


Stage 4: Growth

Investment size – over £ 250 k

Risk to investor - Low

Milestones - Everything is in place and your company is looking to expand and scale

Your GPS system

Emphasis is on Growth, Profitability and Scalability_Sustainability

- by using industry best practises.


Top 1 %

Successful Business model is ALL 3:

- high Tech,

- solid Business best practice, & 

- disciplined Entrepreneurs


Start up stands for:

S calability

T eam

A real need

R evenue (rule breaker)

T hird party validation

U SP (users)

P rototype (MVP)


Important Cs

***Collaboration***Content***Contacts***Cash flows***Concepts

***Competition***Costs***Connection***Customers***Change


Personal Development

Confidence, Discipline, Motivation, Positivity, Optimism, Communication,

Time management, Leadership, Focus, Health, Self-Esteem, Resilience,

Resourcefulness, Teamwork, Proactive, Initiative, Personality, Passion, Character,

Corporate functions

IT, Finance, H.R., Customer services, Governance, Compliance, Marketing,

Sales, Product dev, Project Mgt,  Operations, Enterprise, Export, Risk,

Purchasing and Inventory, Legal, Admin.


Planning and Performance

Forecasting, Monitoring, Metrics, Measurement, Deliverables, Deadlines

Targets/Goals, Achievements


Mentor

Revenue model

Projection, Forecasts, Metrics, cost of Acquisition, Repeat customers


Markets

Supply, Demand, Risk, Size, Segmentation, Disruption, Market research, 

Market data, Market fit, Tracking, Saturation, Maturity, Message, Barriers, 

New markets, Adjacent markets, Market niche

description:
TechBikers was born in 2012 from Google Campus in London as a means for the tech community to put down their laptops and pick up a bike to support charity, network, share ideas and spread the start-up vibe.

Behind TechBikers is Eze Vidra, head of Google Campus, Benjamin Southworth, ex Deputy CEO at Tech City UK, and Abraham Choi, Founder of Decision Analytics and Mark Jennings.

To date we have ridden 640 km and donated almost £100,000 to charity.

At its core is a 3 day 320km ride from Paris to London taking 70 mixed ability riders on a challenging but safe experience, but it is so much more - it is 4 month programme of training rides, group meetings, personal fundraising and support that is shared across social media and in the press, before, during and after the ride.

We apply startup methodologies of agility, programmatic intelligence, hard work and great fun to create a unique, effective and transparent organisation.

description:
ABOUT US

HackerNest is a grassroots nonprofit organization that runs unpretentious community events and epic, meaningful, universally-acclaimed hackathons. Our mission is economic development through technological proliferation. Check us out >>> Facebook  |  Twitter  |  Wikipedia

Connecting people is awesome. And community good breeds fab karma. We cram smart, accomplished techies into a room, often with free drinks. Our relaxed, down-to-earth Tech Socials are now Canada’s largest tech meetups and growing quite quickly internationally. Our membership is diverse and highly technical. Developers, designers, engineers, social media/business folk, entrepreneurs, investors, etc. regularly gather to socialize, talk tech, hear the occasional speaker or watch a demo, and meet future co-founders, employees, funders, and friends.

Our formula: laid back atmosphere + free drinks + brilliant people = fireworks. We're not scienticians, but this seems to work. We became Canada's largest tech meetups in a year, before even leaving Toronto. Today we have "splinter cells" in multiple cities internationally. Our goal is to complement and strengthen existing nerd ecosystems – we come in peace. We hail the ideal of a strong and supportive tech community - pretty much anyone that isn't a jerk can be a part of it, so we have a strict no-douchebag policy.

Interested in running HackerNest in your city? Take a look at the FAQ. Whoa, longest description evaaar. Need to know more? Here's some answers. 

RSVP to get a custom, hand-written nametag. This is important, because people without nametags aren't even really people. There, we said it. :)

Facebook  |  Twitter  |  Wikipedia

SOME DETAILS:

********

When: Pretty darned regularly. Check back!

Format: Relaxed. Hang, talk tech, occasionally a speaker, plot to take over the world, etc.

Where: Usually in the large private office of a tech company (have a venue?)

At any given HackerNest meetup, you may find people who are:

developing incredibly snazzy Ruby (most likely on Rails) applications - heady hardcore designer types - PHP/Perl/.NET/Python/django addicts - ...Fortran devs?! - looking for a tech/entrepreneur/new business story to cover - Objective-C experts and iPhone/iPad/Apple product pundits - engineers and managers and CTOs looking for co-founders to join their angel/VC-backed tech startup - looking to write articles/stories about the obscure, interesting, hilarious hacks you've pulled off - totally oblivious and just wandered in because they heard there was booze (!?) - building a top-secret app out of their basement that's going to change the way the world does X; like "Facebook for Squirrels" - scrambling to find a partner to work with on a well-paying contract that's just a wee bit too much workload for the anticipated deadline - heroes, because they're part of the burgeoning community that will reverse all this insane brain-drain - incredibly talented, smart, entrepreneurial go-getters who are absolutely dangerous to the status quo - pretty bloody interesting, because seriously, if they're coming out for drinks ON A MONDAY (or Tuesday, or Wednesday) NIGHT... they've gotta be.

Chances are, you'll fit right in if you're a(n):

software or hardware hacker/h4ck3r (or maybe just a hack) - coder/developer/programmer/designer, UX-oriented, or just like making things pretty - biotech/electrical/computer or basically any kind of engineer - network/network/system/IT administrator - front/back-end specialist - angel investor - demon investor - venture capitalist - venture communist - tech enthusiast - tech/entrepreneur-oriented media/journalist - OCD blogger/Tweeter - bloodthirsty recruiter looking to poach developers - internet mogul - nerd/geek/freak/tweak - entrepreneur - SEO/SEM pro - writer/project manager/business analyst - 1337 individual - etc., etc.


...and aren't a douchebag. <3

description:
·  Do you have an idea that you want to turn into a mobile app but don’t know how?

·  Don’t know where to get the information you need?

·  Thought it was difficult to get started?

If you have answered YES to any of the above questions then you have come to the right place.



Here's why you should develop apps for iPhone or Android… 

We have developed many apps on different platforms over the years.

Let us tell you why:

·  Both iPhone & Google Play have amazing frameworks to develop on. Developers love them. The platforms offer tremendous power and speed for developing apps.

·  You don't have to create complex apps. Tiny little apps have become the most popular (and profitable!) Small apps mean you can get started cheaply and quickly!

·  You don't have to worry about taking payment from customers.It is taken care of for you. You don't have to worry about merchant accounts. You'll simply get a cheque in the post.

·  You don't need a website.You don't need to host any files. You don't have to worry about customers losing your application. It is all done for you.

·  You don't need to do any promotion (if you don’t want to). It is one thing to build an app. It's another to get people to notice. Since everyone uses the same App Store, you have access to the 10 million iPhone owners, and growing, who can see your app.

Bottom-line: All the sticky, ugly, messy stuff is all taken care of. What does this mean to you? 

You can focus on what you do best: simply creating amazing mobile applications. 


Here's why you should be developing your App right now, today... 

·  At present – customers search for products

·  Future – products will find customer

This means that you can develop your app(s) and the customers will find you.

Do you think you can tap into this opportunity?

Global. We want an international network of HackerNest “splinter cells” to pop up everywhere – from underserved cities to high-growth innovation centers – to rescue nerds from isolated basements, offices, and code tunnel vision.

description:
We’ve heard it a hundred times or more: someone goes on an agile / Scrum / Kanban course, they understand the ideas, but, when they get back to the office, they struggle to implement what they’ve learned. It’s tough. Everyone’s team and organisation is different. There is no one-approach-fits-all. 

Sorry for that.

But there is good news: Scrum & Kanban is here to help. With years of experience working with all types of companies (from start-ups to traditional multi-national companies) in a range of industries (including finance, fashion, tourism, government, recruitment), we know that each situation requires a bespoke approach.

Even better news: we are producing videos and events to help people develop their understanding of Scrum and Kanban, focusing on how to use it in the real world.

description:
What is NetSquared Midlands?

NetSquared Midlands is a regular free event for people interested in using web or mobile technology for social good. Whether you are a charity, community group or nonprofit organization in the traditional sense, a venture capitalist, a programmer, an individual with a great idea, or a social changemaker, NetSquared Midlands is here to help you make connections and create a community around innovating for good in the Midlands. 

These events are great opportunities to learn what others are trying, see successful projects and platforms, hear about developing technologies, make new friends and collaborate on new projects.

Our programme will be a varied mix of open mic unconference sessions, speakers on topics relevant to the sector, show and tell sessions and one to one surgeries. 

NetSquared Midlands is part of a global NetSquared movement of innovators in more than 50 cities around the world.

description:
The Agile Manifesto was written in 2001 and is firmly established in software development industry. It is now an exciting time when the agency landscape is exploding in London and Agile implementation is finding its feet in this new context.
In the Agile spirit of collaboration, interaction and continuous improvement, this Meetup is aimed at people who work in or with agencies of all kinds, from traditional to specialist, creative to tech, in project management, software development or business management roles and are seeking to exchange working experience, tips and general thoughts on how best to create a brand of Agile that works for them, their organisation and their clients.


Looking for SEU for your Scrum Alliance certification? Agile for Agencies is an accredited event!http://members.scrumalliance.org/user_group...


Group rules: Given the effort and often cash that goes into organising free events that have limited space, we ask that attendees that are not able to attend anymore to have the courtesy of letting us know as soon as possible and free their spot. This is also courtesy to people who are on the waiting list.

We are taking names on the door and will strike off NO SHOWS after 3 offenses (i.e. RSVPed YES but didn't show up or contacted us).

description:
We meet monthly to showcase new technology from London and around the world followed by networking. 5-7 presenters show demo of their technology and answer questions (5+5min).

The idea is to promote new technologies to tech-interested public, as well as potential clients, employees and investors. Finally, to provide inspiration and networking opportunities to those who want to find their passion by watching and interacting with others who are pursuing what they love.

Marvel at the latest in cool technology! Watch some slide decks and ask questions!

We seek sponsors and presenters!

Sponsorship plans:

Platinum: Table to set up demo/brochures, Presentation, Logo on the Meetup page, Email campaign with your offering

Gold: Introduction, Logo on the Meetup page, Email campaign with your offering

Silver: Verbal acknowledgement, Logo on the Meetup page

Freemium: Post your updates and events on our FB page and Meetup discussion board.

description: This is a group for those people who spend their days working behind the scenes of the Salesforce setup menu to configure, customise and extend the functionality of Salesforce business applications. Whether you are a member of an in-house team or employed as an external consultant, we all have something in common. That is, keeping up to date with a continually evolving platform and the need to learn and share our experiences of best practice. Those who are not new to the world of Salesforce already know, understand, and often preach WHY Salesforce cloud benefits the businesses which use it. The aim of this group is to bring people together to talk HOW to get the job done and deliver those benefits. The word used to identify people who carry out these tasks on the Salesforce platform is "admin", but as we all know there are many many different roles which sit behind the label. This group is a place for us all to gather, whether the majority of our time is spent on end-user support, or business analysis, or responding to business change that needs additional validation and workflows to be created, or integrating with different platforms using 3rd party tools, the list goes on and on. There is already a strong Salesforce community centred around London, this group aims to serve the needs of Salesforce admins in particular by providing a place to meet face-to-face and build new relationships, share personal experiences and see hands-on examples of Salesforce configuration techniques using all the features. The group will welcome members who are new to the world of Salesforce, or who may be considering in becoming a Salesforce admin in the future. We're going to need more people in order to build all these business applications in the cloud! Welcome #awesomeadmin!

description:
Practical and in-depth debates about data visualisation, advanced analytics and machine learning. Data scientists, BI analysts, statisticians, mathematicians and programmers are all welcome. Feel free to bring your visualisations to share and discuss with the community. Each meeting will feature two or three 30-minute talks followed by Q&As and networking - all in a lovely Soho office with snacks and drinks provided.  

We cover different types of algorithmic and computer generated visualisations of varied datasets. We don't coverer infographics, art and 3d modelling.

Would you like to take the floor? Please get in touch if: 

• you've done a research on visualisation, 

• you've coded/generated a stunning visualisation,

• your organisation has accumulated significant experience in data visualisation and is willing to share the best practices.

All slides are published here: https://speakerdeck.com/advanced_data_visua...

Join and enjoy!

description:
Google Developer Group Leicester meets monthly at Incubate Leicester. We want to attract developers to learn, share and discover more about Google's evolving technologies and APIs. Our meetings will always be free and open to the general public. However, we may have to limit attendance based on interest and the size of our meeting space. So, early RSVPs on this meetup group are encouraged to ensure your spot at upcoming meetings.

Google Developer Groups (GDGs) are for developers who are interested in Google's developer technology; everything from the Android, Chrome, Drive, and Google Cloud platforms, to product APIs like the Cast API,Maps API, and YouTube API.

A GDG can take many forms -- from just a few people getting together to watch our latest video, to large gatherings with demos and tech talks, to events like code sprints and hackathons. However, at the core, GDGs are focused on developers and technical content.

description:
You can join us to help develop Grand Challenge competitions throughout the UK, recent examples include www.Coins-GrandChallenge.com

The purpose of the Grand Challenge campaign is to find entrepreneurs who can leverage exponential technologies to help solve humanity's most severe challenges, including quality education for all, eradicating poverty and food shortages, the provision of clean water, security, global health, sustainable energy production and distribution, and the environment. Prizes to date have included attending Singularity University's Graduate Summer Programme, and various Executive Courses based at NASA Research Park, nr Mountain View in California, along with attending Wired conferences. 

Members will be interested in knowing how they can support this initiative, from helping to mentor and judge competitors, to supporting the organisation of regional competitions throughout the UK including London, and even helping raise sponsorship. Recent sponsors include Aviva, American Express/ AMEX,  Isle of Man Government, Hoxton Ventures, slowXchange, Blue Wire Capital, Isle of Man Government, Wired.

We can meet in central London to discuss more, location depends on the level of interest <br>

description:
This meetup group will be run inside Coventry Makerspace as a Saturday morning Kids Technology Club called Tech4kids.

IMPORTANT: You must be over 18 to signup to this meetup and you must stay with the child in your care while they are attending Tech4kids events.

If you have a child aged before 10-16 that is gifted and talented and wants to learn programming, electronics, robotics, computing then this group is for you. The format will be children guiding children through these activities. Our current instructors are two passionate programmers aged 10 and 20, they will form the team that will promote the learning. 

There will be Makerspace staff onsite but will not be involved in the main learning activities but may be called upon for specialist knowledge around robots and electronics when required. 

Parents are required to remain onsite and provide overall supervision for there children. This requirement may change in time as we adopt the child protection policies that are currently being developed.

description:
Do you understand the basics of agile and Scrum, but wish you had a coach or mentor who you could consult when you need some help? Are you an expert in agile and want to give something extra to the community?

Since starting our mentorship programme, Scrum & Kanban Limited has been inundated with people wanting to get involved. Although we mentor our mentees on an individual basis (accepting a new mentee every 4 months), we wanted to find a way to help others find mentors so we set up this site.


OUR AIM IS TO …

• Provide mentees with someone to talk to when they need help

• Provide mentors with a way of helping individuals in the agile community


We will do this by:

• displaying profiles of mentees and mentors

•  acting as a place where mentees can approach a mentor and/or where mentors can approach a mentee 

• enabling members to send private messages to each other

• providing a place to post questions to the programme community and hold discussions


HOWEVER, IT IS NOT …

•  a fully supervised or moderated programme. We provide this service just to introduce two parties who can help each other; what goes on during the individual mentoring relationship is completely down to the parties involved. We do not take responsibility for any damages, losses or harm done during any relationships that result from introductions through this site. You are fully responsible for your own actions whilst on this site and for your own behaviour and safety off the site too. As an adult, we are assuming that you will take all appropriate precautions to keep yourself and your business safe

• a place to earn money; everyone is doing this for free 

• a place for you to come and show off how much, or who, you know. This is about helping people, not boosting your ego

• a place to advertise your business (even if you are a coaching company) or any other products

• a place to promote events (although, if you have details of an event that you think will benefit people on the mentorship programme, by all means send it through to us. We will then decide if it is appropriate and whether it should be posted) 

• a place to post blogs 

• a job site

If you don't follow these rules, you may be blocked from the site without notice. 


WHAT NEXT?

•  Join the group. In the process, you will be asked various questions which we will then post as your bio for mentors and mentees to read

• Mentees: look through the bios from mentors. If you think one of them fulfils what you are looking for, send them a message through the site 

• Mentors: look through the bios from mentees. If you think you can help one of them, feel free to send them a message through the site 

• Once you have agreed a mentor/mentee relationship, it’s up to you what happens next. Our work is done. Just remember to change your status to “UNAVAILABLE” so that you don’t continue to get contacted.


WHAT ARE THE QUESTIONS WE ASK?

This is a public site, so share only what you are prepared for people to see.

"Do you want to be a mentee or mentor?" - A mentee is someone who is looking for help in their journey to understand agile and/or lean. A mentor is someone who is able to help people along this journey.

“Availability?” - This lets people know how much time you are able to give to this programme. For example, “I can give 1 hour per week (weekday evenings only)”. This can be as open or specific as your life allows. Be honest. You don’t want to end up in a relationship with your mentee/mentor where you keep letting them down. Once you are connected to a mentee/mentor, you must edit your profile to say “UNAVAILABLE”, otherwise you may continue to be contacted.

“About me” - Tell us about yourself. If you are a mentee, tell us what you are looking for in a mentor, what experience you have so far, where you work (and whether employed, self-employed, contractor), where you are hoping to get to, your location, etc. If you are a mentor, tell us what you can offer people, your experience, your location, etc. 

Try to tell us everything you want to ay but in as few words as possible. Nobody wants to read lots of waffle.

BEWARE: This is a public site so only share what you are happy for people to see. Don’t go sharing company secrets.

description:
The Business of IoT

A meetup group looking at the business models, technology platforms and data that are behind the IoT.

Our focus is the business side of IoT: We want bring together established and up-and-coming players in the commercial IoT, to reflect and discuss what needs to happen to leverage the huge potential of connected devices across and build bridges into the often closed ecosystems of different vendors.

Our core themes are

• business models supported by IoT 

• bringing it all together, how to connect data silos, open up and share your data in the ecosystem

• the broader world and how to bring location and physical context together

• devices at scale, meshed networks, NFC, Thread and other emerging standards

• scalable platforms and models - the backend of IoT, how do you deal will billions of events a day, support, customer service

• supporting technologies - what technologies can support business at this scale

description:
This is a community for software developers of all levels of experience who want to better at what they do. It is open to everyone whether you work on the Genome Campus, Cambridge or further afield. 

If you have the desire to work at improving and sharing your skills with like minded people this is the place for you. 

So why the new group? The idea of this group is to complement the excellent work done by similar groups in Cambridge and London. By offering day time events we hope to include people who have vast experience but because of commitments outside are not able to participate in existing communities.

Based on the work done by the Software Craftsmanship communities in both London and Cambridge and aims to follow the principles set out in The Manifesto for Software Craftsmanship:

The Manifesto for Software Craftsmanship
As aspiring Software Craftsmen we are raising the bar of professional software development by practicing it and helping others learn the craft. Through this work we have come to value:

Not only working software, but also well-crafted software
Not only responding to change, but also steadily adding value
Not only individuals and interactions, but also a community of professionals
Not only customer collaboration, but also productive partnerships
That is, in pursuit of the items on the left we have found the items on the right to be indispensable..

description:
We’re a networking group built to establish awesome relationships, discuss great ideas, and educate the local AdTech community and have fun while doing it.  We are part of the global family of AdTech Meetup which unites the cities of London, Denver/Boulder, San Fransico and Sidney.  


If you’re passionate about applying technology to improve the way consumers connect with brands online you’ve come to the right place.


We've designed the meetup to be relevant to advertising technology (AdTech) and Digital Marketing aficionados. Attendees include industry observers, developers, employees at AdTech companies, agencies and other digital marketing companies.


Our interests aren't just limited to AdTech. Through our meetup we will be exploring the bleeding edge of technology across multiple industries and inviting speakers from both the AdTech sphere and far far beyond.


Format is subject to change but usually 2 speakers 15 minutes each about something they are passionate about (not a sales pitch!).


We're looking for:

• Sponsors for the event;

• Speakers who have an interesting perspective on the industry to share.

You can always contact us at adtechmeetuplondon@gmail.com if you'd like to help out in any way.



Thanks and we are looking forward seeing you,

The AdTech Meetup London team.


Find more about what we do:

www.adtechmeetup.com

www.linkedin.com/company/adtech-meetup-london

www.facebook.com/adtechmeetuplondon

@adtechmeetup @adtechmeetupuk @4dmbrown @xlitt @tonyjayfrank @blagorodnas

description:

description:
The worlds of hackers and journalists are coming together as reporting goes digital and Internet companies become media empires.

Journalists call themselves "hacks," someone who can churn out words in any situation. Hackers use the digital equivalent of duct tape to whip out code. Hacker-journalists try and bridge the two worlds.

This group is to bring all these people together -- those who are working to help people make sense of their world. It's for hackers exploring technologies to filter and visualize information, and for journalists who use technology to find and tell stories. In the age of information overload, all their work has become even more crucial.

This group aims to help members find inspiration and think in new directions, bringing together potential collaborators for projects and new ventures.

Please also check out our blog at http://hackshackers.com

Help us build the future of media!

description:
This group is for people who are working on or interested in 3D computer vision software/algorithm development and it's applications. With ever cheaper and available sensors, computers, GPUs, HPC, cloud computing and open source software development it's easier than ever to implement sophisticated 3D vision tasks across a huge range of application domains such as robotics, autonomous vehicles, drones/UAVs, industrial inspection and Earth observation satellites.

This group aims to gather a community of researchers, start-ups, hackers and anyone with an interest in 3D vision developments to show-case their projects, give talks and socialise over drinks.

This is a new group, so if you are interested in giving a talk or demo, have ideas for great speakers, or you would like to sponsor a venue/drinks etc then get in touch!

description:
We are on a mission to build a great island tech community in Guernsey and the Channel Islands. 

Join the geeky-creative-designer-techy-startup crowd of Guernsey! 

Our FIRST MISSION is to act as a kind of tech dating-agency and to simply get people to meet each other. This is the simplest and least expensive form of sparking creativity and ideas – get great people together in one room and get out of their way. We want to discover all the talented developers, designers and entrepreneurs out there. 

Our SECOND MISSION is to help catalyse the development of the community from the bottom-up by working on projects together like hackathons, startup weekends, community projects and our own startup ideas. We want to build the right relationships, experience and expertise that will become building blocks for startups of the future. 

We’ve started by organising regular meet-ups. We are a community for the community and we welcome anyone to rise up and organise or (un)organise anything they feel passionate about. 

Come and meet the community over beer or coffee and see where it takes you.

description:
A meetup for systems administrators, site reliability engineers, data center operators, DevOps-minded folks, SaltStack customers, users and contributors. SaltStack is software used for enterprise-scale infrastructure automation, cloud orchestration and application deployment and configuration management. The Salt open source software project was written in Python and according to GitHub is one of the largest and most active open source projects in the world. SaltStack is used by Web-scale IT organizations like LinkedIn, Hulu, Salesforce.com, NASA JPL, Clemson University, Photobucket, XMission, and thousands more. 

We are looking for group members who are interested in sharing and participating by giving talks and SaltStack use case demonstrations and by sharing lessons learned and good SaltStack practices. Please let us know if you'd be willing to give a talk at an upcoming SaltStack London meetup, or request a topic that you'd like to be addressed.

description:
This is a group for people interested in Product Lifecycle Management or PLM to meet up, network, share experiences & best practises and learn from others in the same industry. 

The aim is to keep things very informal and it’s for anybody (Managers, PLM practitioners, consultants etc) who are planning, working towards or working on real life PLM implementations using PLM technologies such as Teamcenter, Aras, Windchill, Enovia etc..  to name but a few).

The focus is on sharing practical insights, best practises & experiences with regard to what works and what doesn't as opposed to the usual sales and marketing blurb..

It’s also a good way for people new to PLM, and perhaps working on PLM projects for the first time, to learn from more experienced PLM people.

We do web meetings on interesting topics usually based around a presentation followed by an open discussion.  The aim is to keep these groups quite small so that we can have a good interactive discussion. So be prepared to participate.

We also hold regular face to face meetings at convenient venues around the world.  Usually there is a short presentation or two on interesting topics followed by drinks and informal networking.

description:
Leith Lives is a collaborative community project. It’s about Leith – past, present and future. It’s about identity and heritage, about coming together (both online and offline), about promotion and action, and much more.

The Leith Lives website is being designed as a wiki, so that anyone will be able to share their knowledge, memories and ideas and there will also be a regular Meetup for people to discuss, plan and develop ideas together.

We hope you’ll join us. The project is still in its early stages and contributions to both project direction and implementation are very welcome.

All New Relic users or those interested are welcome!

description:
With the world’s largest targetable footprint of over 1 billion devices, Imagination delivers the industry’s leading solutions for mobile and beyond. 


Our PowerVR SGX and Rogue families have been used by chip vendors like Allwinner, Intel, LG, MediaTek, Renesas, Rockchip, Samsung, Sony, Texas Instruments and power some of the most iconic consumer products available today. 


MIPS developers are at the forefront of innovation in markets ranging from deeply embedded and microcontroller applications to high-performance 64-bit processing, across a range of operating systems, including Linux, Firefox OS and Android. Please join this group to find out about our events, presentations, interactive sessions and opportunities to meet key members of the Imagination developer team.

description:
Hi, thanks for having a read through our group.  We're a business based in South West London and we are going to be running a series of talks.  These will be based around Mobile Technology, from software development through to strategy and beyond.

Our staff have great experience of working with enterprise sized clients, delivering projects that really make a difference to these organisations.  We've also got a number of "friends" of Chelsea Apps who will be appearing over the course of these talks.

Anyone and everyone is welcome.  Even if you are just interested in finding out a little bit more.  They'll be a talk or two, some questions and afterwards a beer if you'd like.  We'd love to meet all our peers from within the industry and if you'd like to come and talk to us about what you've been up to then feel free.

We are going to vary the locations to give everyone a chance to get to the meetings, so keep an eye on the meet-ups to make sure you're clear on the location.

Thanks

Nick

description:
Welcome to Data Analytics & Business Intelligence social group.

The purpose of DABI London Group is helping business people to enable a better data insights and working with information. Together with business people we will focus on the data insights challenges, how we work with the data and how to unlock insights in the data. We will be looking on ideas how to get more from Data Analytics and Business Intelligence.

We welcome people from the business who are rather users (all rank users) of the technology than the IT experts. The typical group member is not an IT guy but our group member is from the business having role such as a data analyst; a business analyst; business owner; a entrepreneur; a manager; a senior executive; a business decision maker; but main characteristic is that our group member uses data insights and analytics for driving her/his business. People from marketing, sales, performance management, marketing, business development roles areas are very welcome.

The main goals are:

- Discussing the DA & BI business scenarios business people are challenged now.

- Work-shopping how to address that business scenarios and look on technology how it can help.

- Helping business people to sort out challenges with the DA & BI tools.

- Presenting DA & BI tools features focusing on business drivers aspects.

- Looking on DA&BI challenges and how to address these with the Microsoft BI stack.  

We'll be presenting, discussing, work-shopping about the data analytics, business intelligence, data insights, visualisations and also how to tame the technical tools for addressing business needs.

Because the group organiser has an extensive experience with Microsoft BI stack, this group technology focus is mostly around Microsoft technology (such as Excel, SQL, Power BI, SSAS, SSIS, cubes, Office 365, Yammer and many others tools). But please mind that we don't focus on technical discussions only. DABI London Group is focused on business views and needs with technical aspects and looking how the technology brings the value for business and life.  

If you want to enter group you will be asked 5 simple questions. We appreciate your contribution and we want to thank you for answering the group entering questions. Your answers help us to better define the focus and session agenda.

Looking forward seeing you on our meetups!

Jozef

description:
This is a group for anyone interested in software and systems performance.

Themes may include:

- Measurement : you can't improve what you don't measure. How do we know whether our measurements are useful, accurate, correct? 

- Methods : any methods available to help design with performance in mind, or to diagnose issues.

- Discussions on various technologies, runtimes and languages, with a focus on performance. What data structures / Algorithms used, etc

- Simulation : volume testing methods and tools, other simulation tools

- Analytic methods/models : Typically requires a good level of Maths. Errors are regularly found in blogs and talks demonstrating how this are can be particularly challenging. However, it can be much cheaper than simulation, and provide results where simulation can't.

- Optimisation : methods/tools. profiling, instrumenting, etc

description:
GOTO Nights are designed for people who want to stay up to date with the latest tools, technologies, processes and practices in the software industry.

GOTO Nights are free evening events driven by involvement from both speakers and participants. Come along to learn something new and network with your peers! We will provide you with a first class speaker - all you have to do is show up!!

GOTO Nights provide you with an opportunity to:

• Hear world-class speakers

• Learn about the latest trends

• Reach beyond your current language, platform, or practices

• Increase your technical depth and breadth

• Expand your professional network

• Share your experience and expertise with others

• Connect with the global software community

We cover a vast range of topics on our meetups, and if you have a topic you are keen to learn more about, please let us know and we'll try to organise a talk.

description: Leicester Hackspace, a venue for makers of digital, electronic, mechanical and creative projects, opened on 1st March 2014. Like other Hackspaces across the country, we are working to build a community of practical and creative people and provide them with a place to pursue their projects, share techniques and concepts and learn new skills. We have a space in Makers Yard with access to bike repair equipment, computers, a 3D printer, 3D miller/scanner, power tools and many other resources. This space is open to members 24 hours a day. We also run special courses and events, in programming, arduino, electronics, soldering, and more, which are open to members of the public.

description:
This is a group for anyone interested in Wearable Tech - IoT (Internet of Things) IoE (Internet of Everything) and their integration in all aspects of life: Smart Cities, Autonomous Cars, Fashion Technology, Digital Health, etc

Relaxed, open discussions about wearable tech integration and deployment in all verticals: healthcare, fashion, insurance, auto, constructions, media. From 3d printed smart sensors to clothing embedded sensors, from medically approved ingestible sensors to implantables. Feel free to bring up your latest ideas, partnership proposals, emerging tech news, even robotics, AI, VR and AR.

All "skills and levels" are more than welcome. Looking forward to exploring this beautiful world of connected objects with you all, in a kind, warm and friendly environment. 

Just grab a coffee and speak a common language, "Wearable Tech"

description: OWASP, the Open Web Application Security Project, is an open community dedicated to enabling organizations to conceive, develop, acquire, operate, and maintain applications that can be trusted. All of the OWASP tools, documents, forums, and chapters are free and open to anyone interested in improving application security. We advocate approaching application security as a people, process, and technology problem because the most effective approaches to application security include improvements in all of these areas. We can be found at www.owasp.org. Local chapters provide a totally free meeting place for anyone interested in application security from three perspectives - builders, breakers and defenders. So come along to Belfast chapter meetings if you would like to hear about, or share information with the community on how to ethically hack your own systems, how to defend your applications and how to build security into your applications. Chapter meetings also provide a great opportunity to meet like-minded people with similar interests for general discussion, chit-chat and banter! Chapter website: https://www.owasp.org/index.php/Belfast Mailing list: https://lists.owasp.org/mailman/listinfo/owasp-Belfast Although chapter meetings are provided free of charge, OWASP membership is encouraged. Besides supporting the organisation overall and your local chapter, membership funds will provide the holder with benefits in other areas such as free/discounted entry to conferences, etc.

description:
Meet other developers and ops engineers using Docker in Bristol. Docker is an open platform for developers and sysadmins to build, ship, and run distributed applications. Consisting of Docker Engine, a portable, lightweight runtime and packaging tool, and Docker Hub, a cloud service for sharing applications and automating workflows, Docker enables apps to be quickly assembled from components and eliminates the friction between development, QA, and production environments. As a result, IT can ship faster and run the same app, unchanged, on laptops, data center VMs, and any cloud.

Learn more about Docker at http://www.docker.com

description:
This group is primarily but not exclusively aimed at BOND (www.bond.org.uk) T4D group members. The meetup group is a supplement to the T4D group section on the myBond platform. Non-BOND members are welcome, in particular academics, bloggers/journalists and private sector partners.  The groups purpose is described below:

The speed of technological change is rapid, opening up new opportunities and capabilities but also creating new challenges. It is important to understand the impact that such technologies can have on peoples’ lives and on the work of development agencies.  Meetings planned with the following goals:

• To discuss developments related to Technology for Development

• To provide information on emerging trends in technological innovation (eg. Machine-to-machine technology)

• To share best practice and worst practice (why projects don’t work) including case studiesTo provide information on funding and projects/initiatives being undertaken so as to avoid duplication and foster partnerships.

• To maximise Bond members’ reach with stakeholders such as universities and corporations.

To foster relationships with funders of technology-related projects

description:
An ecosystem is a complex web of interdependent agents and relationships aimed to create and allocate personal and business value. The need for integration between intelligent devices , people and enterprises capabilities has become even more critical. Innovation, availability of big data, accesses to personal contexts and contexts evolution are some of the key drivers solution of humans and objects ecological communities. The current challenges in certain sectors, such as Health, Fitness, Energy and Environment, have created the need not only for integration, but a true network of distribute controls and information exchange. The new age of ecosystems In today’s digital world requires new technologies, a broad use of Big Data and Analytics Consumers are forming an ever-more insatiable desire for sophisticated and compelling experiences in all aspects of their lives.
To make real every mentioned we need an evolution of cloud architectural solution based on a system bus that manages messages in real time. To a higher level, agents are aggregated and integrated in groups that constitute the ecosystems.

Meetup scope
We want to create an active group to analyze the specific aspects of Ecosystems, IoT and Personal Big Data science. The objective is to discuss how a person can have a generalizable extraction of knowledge and recommendation from personal cloud data generated by his devices to improve the everyday life quality where the personal cloud is integrated in an ecosystem. The purpose of meetup is explore such complexities creating capabilities in a new and fascinating IT field.

description:

description: Leicester Data Hacking and Visualization Meetup is a community of people interested in manipulating data and visualization. We explore the full range of techniques for converting raw data into visible, shareable insights. We use techniques like scripting languages to collect and manipulate data. Representing data in databases (big or small), several of which are schema-less (NoSQL), or even in files from plain old CSV to those stored across large clusters. Feel free to participate if you are out to start learning, or a long time data miner (before it was even called data science). Your interest in data could be from open government, through business insights, to scientific computing. It could just be putting information on a timeline, showing connections or creating graphics purely for their aesthetics via very simple algorithms.

description:
The internet of things is the future of the internet where ordinary objects will be given senses, intelligence and the power to influence their environment. Objects will also be connected - having conversations between themselves as much as with humans. Ordinary objects will all have the potential to become enchanted objects with magical powers.

Vast amounts of data will be generated by billions of connected objects. There is much talk about IoT and how this data will allow machines to make the world more metricated and efficient. There is little talk about how it could affect and be effected by Arts & Entertainment. I'm thinking about Smart Art and 'Smartertainment'.

I created this group as a platform for people to talk about their ideas or simply listen to others who do. I'd like to create a meetup of forward, lateral and backward thinking people to share knowledge, ideas and inspiration about IoT and Arts & Entertainment. Ultimately I would like this group to spin off collaborations to actively play around with IoT technologies to support, enhance or revolutionise Art & Entertainment.

description:
Leeds Hackspace

We are a community / social group for hackers, makers and doers with the intention of socialising, creating, and potentially make amazing things in a space/workshop with access to tools that you may otherwise not be able to have hands-on with thanks to the contributions and communal efforts of its members.

We are entirely membership run and funded, it is a not-for-profit so every penny made goes back into providing services and facilities for its members, it is run by members for members with a little direction from appointed directors.

This means we can have amazing tools such as a laser cutter, metal lathe, computer systems, welding kit, various saws, a 3D printer or two, a vinyl cutter and a silly amount of electronics, with some quad copters thrown in.

We would love to be and do that much more, which is why you should come along to an open night and make it what you want it to be, because that's how we all started, too.

description:
Calling all open data and transparency activists to join us every last Wednesday of the month for liberating data and lightening talks. Whether you can write a few lines of code to write a bot, or a journalist who is interested in covering stories on transparency, or a campaigner who champions an open and free world - come along to meet like-minded people and use open data to change the world.

If you are an NGO who would like to suggest a mission for these meetups - do get in touch at hera@opencorporates.com

description:
Hello my name is Imran. I am a self taught programmer for the web with a keen interest in Javascript for both front and back-end development. I know a thing or two about the language but I don't know a whole lot more. It's the sort of language that people avoid learning for it's bad parts, but it's a language that you cant avoid if you want to program anything for the web.

This group is for anyone working with Javascript, whatever your experience or domain. I am particular keen for people who would like to learn how to be a web developer/programmer to come along and would be happy to share my experiences and provide any (opinionated) guidance.

Below is a selection of videos that might inspire you to want to learn more.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FRURtW5qXI

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zeKNXaM2fsA

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Lj4xPkrTPKs

Yes I know you're wondering, what happened to Lutech? Well we had a few meetings and it didn't really take off, perhaps it was body odour :p The Meetup group as it was was too broad in it's scope. This is an effort to make it more focused and since I'm paying the dues here I've decided to focus on the thing I would like to be better at.

description:
UX for Change is a London-based meetup, dedicated to bringing the UX design community together in order to tackle problems from any non-industry related fields, such as education, charities and the public sector. 

The format of this meetup is as follows: 

- A speaker from one of these fields will present a challenge to the audience.

- A group of seasoned UX Designer panelists will then identify where UX methodologies and artifacts can be used to tackle this challenge. 

- Immediately after the delegates will work in teams with the main purpose of applying their own experience as well as the suggestions provided by the panel into an actual deliverable (paper sketch or a digital prototype).

The main mission of UX for Change is to create a platform, where UX designers can come together and make a difference in communities where there is little to none UX design resources and where their involvement would make a significant difference to their day-to-day experience. 

This meetup is produced by Axure London.

description:
What is Couchbase?

Couchbase is the company behind Couchbase open source project, a vibrant community of developers and users of Couchbase document-oriented database technology. 

Couchbase Server is a packaged version of Couchbase technology that’s available in Community and Enterprise Editions. Couchbase is known for easy scalability, consistent high performance, 24x365 availability, and a flexible data model. 

Companies like AOL, Cisco, Concur, LinkedIn, Orbitz, Salesforce.com, Shuffle Master, Zynga and hundreds of others around the world use Couchbase Server for their interactive web and mobile applications.

Sign up to our Couchbase Developer Newsletter

description:
CodeUp Manchester is a mentoring program for adults who would like to learn how to code for free. Once a month we provide a workspace for people with no programming skills to come and learn the basics, with mentors available to answer your questions and help you on your way. Our sessions will also be suitable for people with basic skills who need support to develop them, and even for people with intermediate or advanced skills who just want to come along to a space where everyone is immersed in code!

We are currently running sessions on the 2nd Monday of the month at the Code Computer Love offices in the Northern Quarter, near Piccadilly Gardens.. 

If you have any suggestions on what you would like to see in these sessions, or if you would like to join us as a mentor, please contact the organisers!

description:
Google Developer Group Oxford (GDG Oxford) is the community for Google Developers in Oxfordshire.

Google products are an essential part of every developer’s toolkit, making things faster, more intuitive, powerful and reliable. Google Developer Groups help you learn from your peers and Google expert Developers, find out what’s new and share ideas.

Sub-groups:
Angular & Web: AngularJS and Chrome DevTools make the web dynamic
Android & Mobile: Android Studio, Firebase, Dart and Android for Work
Cloud Platform: The easy way to deploy software in the cloud and scale it worldwide
Marketing: Ads and Analytics to engage customers and make the web really work for business
Connection: Google +, Hangouts, Photos, Cast, Gmail, YouTube, Android TV
Things: Nest and other connected devices
Future: Glass, Wearables, Self-driving cars, Virtual Reality and more - be amazed by the possibilities

It also has four specialism areas...
Work: Docs, Sheets, Slides... make work easy and collaborative
Health: Genomics, Fit and Calico
Education: Apps for Education, Classroom Tools, Class Content and Educator
Startups: Helping emerging companies with ideas, technical advice, infrastructure, mentoring etc.

GDG Oxford meets several times each month in Oxford. We have created DevSpace - a community space in Osney Mead for developers, Datascientists and Startups. We also run Ox4Dev - a festival for developers.

Our meetings will, where possible, be free and open. We aim to work closely with Universities, Business Schools, Technical Colleges and Companies in the area. We co-host, help and work with with other developer and technical skills groups - Java, Python, Javascript, DataScience, Biotech etc. We like to give back to communities and help Not for Profit Groups and Charities.

Don’t be frightened
Developers aren’t all experienced full-time employees for enterprise companies - business people trying to design better websites, create an app or get on the cloud. We all have to learn - students are welcome to join our Future Developer programme to gain valuable business experience as well as technical skills. And our Develop the Developer Programme will add depth and breadth to your skillset.

NB: we advise on methods and products we believe are best, not to maximise sales of Google products or services. GDG Oxford is an independent group; activities and opinions expressed here should in no way be linked to Google, the corporation.

description:
This group is aimed at anyone within the Cambridge area who wants to know more about cloud computing and Amazon Web Services , and network with like-minded people. Whether you are C-Level, a techie or in a business or management role, there will be something here for you. 

We have both informal - usually pub - meetings, and more organised meetings.

At the organised meetings, we'll have a schedule, with presentations on cloud computing in general, and Amazon Web Services in particular. They'll be covering a range of levels, from beginner through to guru.

There might be an UnPanel - Google it! - and probably food and drink provided by sponsors. (Veggie food and non-alcoholic drinks included, of course.)

Oh, and if we can get enough people interested, we might even put in a team for the Dragon Boat races!

This is one of the youngest of the AWS User Groups around the country, so you tell us how you like it.

description:
The Cardiff R User Group (CaRdiff) is aimed at folks looking to do data analysis more effectively. 

R is an open source language for analysing data, statistics, visualisation and much, much more. It's a great language to have under your belt - if you're a non-techy it extends your Excel and SAS skills and for techies it allows easy data processing and presentation on the front-end.

Still in it's formative stages this group will cover the topics we want to know about but plans include shiny, web services, data.table, setting up Linux infrastructures, parallel processing and more.

Whether brand new to R and curious, or an Rfficianado, this group is for you!

description:

This Meetup is for anyone using or interested in using the Ionic, a beautiful, open source front-end SDK for developing hybrid mobile apps with HTML5.

If you would like to present something related to Ionic at an upcoming event, please email us at ionicuk@gmail.com


-- Code of Conduct --

Ionic UK is dedicated to providing a harassment-free conference experience for everyone, regardless of gender, gender identity and expression, age, sexual orientation, disability, physical appearance, body size, race, or religion (or lack thereof). We do not tolerate harassment of event participants in any form. Sexual language and imagery is not appropriate for any conference venue, including talks, workshops, parties, Twitter and other online media. Event participants violating these rules may be sanctioned or expelled from the event and all future event at the discretion of the organisers. (adapted from confcodeofconduct.com)

This is a group for enthusiasts of robotics technology!

We think robotics and the related areas of AI, machine learning and computer vision have the potential to transform and improve quality of life and help a number of vital industries. London is a leading centre for robotics research and lots of new and exciting startups are appearing. 

This is a group for people from any background or discipline wanting to learn about the latest developments and discover new ways to apply robotics technology to help solve problems.

Our meetups will be informal and social. There'll be demos / showcases of robotics in action and an opportunity to meet fellow robotics enthusiasts.

This group was created by the team behind FlyWave, a London based startup that's creating a data analysis platform for drone operators.

description:
Smarter London is a monthly grassroots multi-city salon for talking, demoing, sharing, case-studies, prototypes, applications, networks, best practices, investment/funding opportunities, successes and failures in projects or pilots involved in making our cities smarter and issues facing it.

We are starting in London and bringing this format to other cities interested in jointly building an inter-disciplinary tech, business, city and startup community interested in co-creating smarter cities with city officials, planners, tech service providers and community interest groups. If you are a developer, designer, investor, city planner, community expert, involved in public policy, urban data modeler, architect, startup looking at getting involved and connected to a budding entrepreniural smarter city community – this is your meetup. 

Find us at @D4SC on Twitter and use #SmarterLondon for interesting pilots, projects, people, funding opportunities, jobs or anything related to making London Smarter by involving people, technology, data and city systems both at grassroots and at scale. We want to bring big and little data together.

Get in touch with Priya  (@priyascape or priya dot prakash at design4socialchange dot com) if you’d like to share something with this community or to partner/sponsor one of our meetups – Currently exploring a number of spaces to run this meetup including Level 39.

description:
A meet-up for everyone who enjoys planning, designing, developing or using technology that is accessible and usable by everyone.

The monthly free meet-ups usually on the last Wednesday each month to discuss Accessibility-related topics, give the opportunity to learn more, develop your own skills, and to network with like-minded people, all in a friendly environment.

The group & meet-ups are helped by a small group of individuals interested in encouraging and promoting Accessibility for all: Leonie Watson, Oliver Davies, Indu Kaila, Katie Grant, Pete Britain, Jon Gibbins, Alastair Campbell.

Also, do have a look at the main Accessible Bristol website.

We're looking for sponsorship for our future meet-ups (for the venue hire, refreshments) - if you're interested in being a Sponsor, do let us know.


Thanks to our event sponsors PowerMapper Accessibility Software, Dig Inclusion, LJ Watson Consulting, and the Engine Shed

description:
Eris Industries makes the tools for developers to build secure distributed computing systems for whatever purpose they can imagine. These tools are the distributed application server, or Decerver, and our bespoke smart contract-enabled, smart contract-controlled blockchain design, called Thelonious. They're ready-to-use, right now, at  https://decerver.io/tutorials . 

This MeetUp group is administered by the corporate bods at Eris Industries and a few independent developers who've taken a keen interest in using our stuff. 

Hang out, build stuff, have fun!

description:
Technology is rapidly transforming medicine and Medicine is been rapidly transformed by technology!


We, MedTech developers, are part of the technology development in Medicine and watching medical technology transform the world. We believe medical technology is the current and the future of medical diagnosis, treatment and innovation. From a single medical image, we can tell alot. For example, the different bones, tissues, muscles e.t.c From a 3D video dataset, we can tell alot. For example, visualise the abnormal heart beats in 4D (3D space and time). From a multi dimensional data set, we can tell infinite things. For example, we can find new patterns for detecting cancer. We can apply new algorithm to control effective drug delivery herapy. We can use machine learning to discover hidden disease pattern we never knew before. We can.... do ALOT NOW! 


We are excited to meet up with other MedTech Developers who are changing the world and challenging the status quo. Also, we are excited to learn more about MedTech techology by tackling real problem and running real projects. We are changing the world by meeting up!

description:
Being based in Chester we realise that there are precious few opportunities for developers to get together and learn about new things. In 2015 our New Years Resolution at Footsqueek is to see if we can change that! We've therefore decided to organise a regular bi-monthly hackathon and open it up to everyone!

The concept is really simple. Each hack will have a theme; participants, working in teams will have 24 hours to develop and submit a product related to the theme. The general public will then be invited to vote for their favourite product via facebook and the winning team will receive prizes.

More information at www.footsqueek.co.uk/Events/HackDay.aspx

description:
RE.WORK combines entrepreneurship, technology and science to solve some of the world's greatest challenges using emerging technology. We showcase the opportunities of exponentially accelerating technologies and their impact on business and society.
