Do you know how to leverage new technologies such as the internet of things, sensors, 3D printing, nanotechnology, biotechnology, artificial intelligence? How can you apply emerging research to solve our biggest challenges such as unprecedented urbanisation levels, efficient healthcare, education for all, sustainable energy solutions and food for all?

description:
Meet other engineers interested in Google Kubernetes. 

Kubernetes is an open source system for managing containerized applications across multiple hosts, providing basic mechanisms for deployment, maintenance, and scaling of applications. 

Kubernetes builds upon a decade and a half of experience at Google running production workloads at scale, combined with best-of-breed ideas and practices from the community.

description: Google Dart is a fresh ECMAscript web language for client-side and server-side software development. It has features similar to NodeJS but its syntax and technology, in general, is designed from ground up to suit the needs of web development. It transpiles to javascript, retaining its best parts while delivering almost double the performance on server-side than NodeJS. It also works perfectly fine with existing javascript libraries. Startups have already started using Google Dart as their primary language.

description:
The Cambridge .NET User Group is a community of professional .NET developers with a strong passion in building high quality software using Microsoft platforms and technologies. 

Join our general discussions on Slack: https://dotnetcambridge.herokuapp.com/
You can also send a mail to our mailing list dotnetcambridge-list@meetup.com  
See our past discussions on Mailing List Archive and on the Message Board.

COMMUNITY MANIFESTO

- Members Engagement over number of members
- Members Contribution over external experts contribution
- Constant Knowledge Sharing over sporadic events
- Collaborative learning over self-promotion
- .NET Technologies over other technologies
- Free Events over paid events
- Respect and humilty over technical competence

We believe in the power of collaborative learning and we love sharing our knowledge and experiences with other members of our community. We love to discuss, share opinions, learn from mistakes and professionally grow together. We are also open minded developers curious to explore trending technologies and languages outside the Microsoft world, learn and compare them with the familiar tools we use everyday on the job. 

Read more about our principles.

Who should join us?
Professional .NET developers (even if you don't live in Cambridge).

Why a new community?
There a lot of very good developer communities in Cambridge but there is no community targeting specifically .NET developers. Ideally the community should be made of people that are working on .NET everyday and that are eager to learn and develop themselves through collaborative learning and presenting. There is no limit in terms of topics to discuss but we will look at them from the eyes of people who work with Microsoft technologies for the majority of their working time.

Twitter: @dotnetcambridge

What about recruiters?

Recruiters are treated as any other members and are welcome to join the group and attend our events to learn and build their network but they need to agree on a code of conduct.

If you are a recruiter:

 - You must not post job ads in the discussion forum or in the mailing list
 - You must not spam the group sending job ads to our members via private messages
 - You can talk about job opportunities with interested people during networking breaks at our events

If you are not a recruiter:

 - Report to the organizers if you receive any unwelcome private message
 - Report to the organizers any unwelcome behavior during our events
 - Report to the organizers any general concern you have about the future of the community

After repeated violations of these rules we will send a notice and if the offending behavior continue we will ask you to leave our community.

description:
@GROW we have built an environment where diverse creative types from designers, digital natives and artisans come together to design, be disruptive and do stuff! The space is specifically designed for those creatives who want to FUSE TECHNOLOGY and CREATIVITY together to make their dreams become a reality.

Come and join us if...

•   You are the kind of person who wants to actually ‘do’ and ‘create’ stuff and not just talk about doing stuff

•   You enjoy getting hands on with your art, craft or design?

•   You enjoy experimenting and using technology…but perhaps don’t have the knowhow, or can’t afford and justify tech in your own business?

•   You have a specific idea and want to prototype it?

•   Or you are simply intrigued to know more about how you can use technology in your creative projects – or make your techie/hacker projects more beautiful?

This Meetup Group will showcase specific ‘Doers’ along with all kinds of creative practices and technology. We will encourage playfulness and experimentation, foster collaboration and enable you to meet like-minded people who are passionate to make things happen!!

Come and join us at GROW@GreenPark for regular Meetups and great opportunities to experience the space.

Simone & Mark

description:
So Make It is a non-profit Makerspace in Southampton, UK – a friendly and inclusive place for people who like making things to sharing knowledge, experience and tools. 

The interests of the current membership focus on subjects of wood- and metal-work, costume design, craft, photography and technology (3D printing, microcontrollers (Arduino, etc), robotics, quad-copters, home automation, computers (Raspberry Pi, etc) and programming). We have a significant number of tools available to facilitate these activities and our members are often willing to lend their own personal tools too.

Membership is not required to use the space, please just pop in during our Opening Hours and see what we’re about; hopefully you might consider joining us on our journey to bring maker-culture to everyone!

Come join us!

description:
Software on the Rocks blends two disciplines renowned for their mastery and craftsmanship: great software and fine drinks. Inspired by the open spaces format, we'll explore the patterns and practices that make great software great... all whilst enjoying an ale, Scotch, or anything else the pub has to offer.

While this obviously covers a broad range of topics, we'll theme some events around simplicity in design and process, effective software teams, agile/lean mindsets, usability, transitioning to continuous delivery / DevOps, etc. Basically, all the parts of development that support and lay the groundwork for great software. All types of software professionals are welcome and encouraged -- part of the experience will be learning and sharing perspectives from folks outside your immediate area of expertise.

description:
We're a bunch of software developers that love to code, play, learn, improve and eat pizza!

Every month we meet up in order to practice code katas, clean code, software craftsmanship, pair programming, Test-Driven Development and learn from each other for an hour or two. As it's after work, food and drinks are provided :)

If you'd like to learn more about Software Craftsmanship, the best place to start is 'What Is Software Design?' by Jack Reeves (use Google). If you'd like more in-depth material, Pete McBreen's Book: 'Software Craftsmanship: the new imperative' is great start.

description:
This is a group for anyone interested in having a website for blogging or business. 

Please take a look at our other well established group meetup.com/websitebuildingforbeginners as we are currently merging to serve the varied needs and interests of members.

Depending on demand, meetings for Websites 'n Blogs will be tailored to all skill levels and interests of those who'd like to attend. From those completely new to websites or blogging, to experts wishing to explore and exchange ideas that uncover the full power of having a website and blogging platform. 

It's a safe environment that allows for newbies wishing to learn with plenty of help to get started. 

An ideal hub and resource for more experienced bloggers or business owners who are. or want to take their business online. 

Come and see why WordPress is the best free Content Management System for your website or blog, with lots of tips, tricks and everything you need in one place.

We can also offer help with using other web design platforms, including Weebly, Mobirise, and others.

Please feel free to get in touch and say Hi!

Ken & Suzanne

West Wales Web

Pembrokeshire Life Online

description:
Bristol Games Hub, officially opened by industry legend Ian Livingstone, is a non-profit organisation that provides working space in Bristol where game developers and academics come together under one roof to create and study games. Our vision is of a centre of excellence in games development that attracts new business and job opportunities for Bristol’s thriving games development community.

The Hub is for games development companies, freelancers and academics working on any game-related activity. All funds raised are put straight back into developing the space, supporting the Hub’s residents and the wider South West games community. 

We run meetups on the last Thursday of the month for the community, or people who would like to learn more about video games production.  These are generally informal but often have a few talks from indies or industry.

description:
Project SAFE (Secure Access For Everyone) aims to create a decentralized and secure Internet 2.0 (whitepaper). The SAFE Network is a secure and fully decentralized data management service. The network is made up from the unused computer resources provided by the network users. By providing resources users earn Safecoins - a digital currency that can be used to access network services. The SAFE Network also supports distributed applications that can be accessed (for free or paid) by the network users. 


More info: 

• MaidSafe Technology Overview

• MaidSafe Official Webpage 

• MaidSafe Discussion Forum 

• MaidSafe Roadmap 

• What's the deal with "Project SAFE" and "MaidSafe"?

description:
Welcome to the first meetup focussed on real development and how to get things done in ServiceNow. It is where developers in the ServiceNow community can get together, network, and meet other developers purely for presenting, discussing and learning the technical, (what some might call) nerdy and geeky aspects of ServiceNow. From simple UI Actions, Client Scripts and Business Rules, etc, through to stuff like mixing phase 1 and 2 Jelly in the same UI page, how to develop your own processor, the best ways for creating Scripted Web Services, developing custom CMS, and of course, some little hacks and tweaks that make our lives that little bit easier.

Whatever level of developer you are in ServiceNow, feel free to join. Ideally, you should be working with ServiceNow at least at Administrator level and have a reasonable understanding of JavaScript.

And finally, we'll also make sure to have developer friendly food and drinks.

Disclaimer: This meetup is not sponsored or affiliated with ServiceNow in any way.

description:
Google Developer Groups Reading and Thames Valley (GDG Reading & Thames Valley) is the community for developers interested in Google technologies in Reading and the Thames Valley, including Bracknell, Wokingham, Maidenhead, Marlow, Newbury, Slough and Windsor. 

Google technologies are an essential part of every developer’s toolkit. Making whatever you develop faster, more intuitive, powerful and reliable. But things move fast and it can be challenging to keep up. Google Developer Groups help you learn from your peers, find out what’s new and share ideas. 


GDG Reading & Thames Valley has several sub-groups: 

• Web Technologies: JavaScript, CSS3, HTML5, libraries, frameworks and tools for building modern Web applications such as AngularJS, Polymer, Chrome, Charts, Material Design, etc... 

• Mobile: Covers Android, Android development and mobile integration with other Google technologies.  

• Cloud Platform: A platform for cloud based services such as: Infrastructure as a Service, Platform as a Service and Software as a Service.. Google Cloud Platform includes App Engine, Compute Engine, Bigquery (Big Data), Cloud Storage, Cloud SQL, etc...

• Connection: Google+, Gmail, Youtube and APIs  

• Apps for Work: A powerful suite of cloud based productivity and collaboration tools. 

• Marketing: Ads and Analytics make the web really work for business. 

• Internet of Things: Nest and connected device APIs 

• Future Technologies: Deepmind, Wearables and more - be amazed by the possibilities.  

• Developer Startups: Helping emerging companies with ideas, technical advice, infrastructure etc. 

GDG Reading and Thames Valley meets monthly at GROW in Green Park in Reading and at various other locations across Berkshire. Regular hackathons, training sessions and events too. 

Let’s Build a Community 

Our meetings will where possible be free and open to the general public. We believe in community and work where possible with Universities, Business Schools, Technical Colleges and Companies in the area. We often co-host with other developer and technical skills groups - Java, Python, Javascript, DataScience, Biotech etc. We like to help Not for Profit Groups and Charities. 

Don’t be frightened 

Developers aren’t all experienced full-time employees for enterprise companies - often they are business people trying to design better websites, create an app or get on the cloud. And we all have to learn - students are very welcome and we can help you gain valuable business experience as well as technical skills. Last but not least - we advise on methods and products we believe are best, not necessarily to maximise sales of Google products or services. 

Follow us:

Google+

Twitter

description:
Can we see the future? Apocalypse, Nirvana or something we can shape to our advantage?
This group is for people who are interested in the future and maybe want to help create it.

Accelerating technological advances will bring radical changes to all of us. Biological technologies like anti-aging, nanotech, genetics and health monitoring. New educational opportunities and methods. Computing, robotics, and geo-engineering are going to make the next few years very exciting - and possibly also very dangerous.

Oxford is uniquely placed to have a high level debate on this. Several departments of Oxford University are dedicated to understanding the future along with Oxford Martin, Said Business School and Oxford Brookes. But it is not just an academic debate. John Radcliffe Hospital is creating the future of Health. Google's Deepmind Project and others are pushing back the boundaries of what's possible. Oxford is the home of DataScience in the UK. And we are pushing the envelope of space exploration, nuclear research and nanotechnology.

Let's explore the possibilities and the ethical, technology and business implications together. Everyone is welcome - the future applies to us all!

description:
This is a group for anyone interested in Functional Programming. All levels of ability and experience are welcome. We meet monthly and together we'll figure out how to rewire our brains to think and code functionally. 


We are the Belfast contingent of the Functional Kats (Dublin) meet-up.  We generally link into their meet-up over Skype and leach all their great content! 

Functional Kats started in January 2014 and has been going since, follow @functionalKats on twitter to learn more. 

Meetups generally begin with a programming challenge. You are encouraged to solve the problem in any language, ideally in collaboration with other attendees. After a break for some refreshments, we then project a selection of the solutions on to the big screen for discussion. 

From time to time we change the format to more of a talk/workshop, given by either a member of the group, or an outside speaker. We try to ensure that talks are tailored to allow for some element of hands on coding.

description:
Lego® Serious Play® Friends & Facilitators welcomes you to our MeetUp Group

We run different kinds of MeetUp:

_____________ 

Come to a Mini MeetUp: A Lego® Serious Play® Workshop for 7 people

Mini MeetUps give small groups of maximum of 7 participants an introduction to Lego® Serious Play® using basic and mid level Lego® Serious Play® application techniques, namely: building individual models, building shared models, creating landscapes and making connections. 

If you're curious about Lego® Serious Play® and what to know more, this free mini meet is for you. 

You can see what one looks like here.

_____________ 

Come to a Bigger MeetUp

We’re just reviewing plans for bigger meetups with our current sponsor, so watch this space for plans for bigger meetups hosted by The App Business.

_____________ 

About the Lego® Serious Play® friends and facilitators MeetUp group. 

This MeetUp group is run with enthusiasm by two trained Lego® Serious Play® facilitators.

We don't work for Lego, and claim no ownership of the brilliant ideas LEGO created. (Read full trademark guidelines). 

_____________

Lego Serious Play MeetUps in other countries and cities

There are Lego Serious Play Groups in:

Germany | Berlin

Canada | Montreal

Holland | Utrecht

Belgium|Leuven

Special administrative region of China | Hong Kong

_____________

Additional Information on Lego® Serious Play®

An excellent book, "Building a Better Business Using the Lego Serious Play Method" (available at Amazon) sets out the history, core ideas and theoretical underpinning of Lego® Serious Play®. It is an easy read, and helps explain why the Lego® Serious Play® method is so powerful. 

Read more about the method and background to Lego® Serious Play® on the Lego website. 

Additionally seriousplaypro.com is a forum of just over 1000 members. It is the place to go to for information on training and certification.

_____________

Respecting Ownership

Please note, Lego® Serious Play® is owned by by LEGO who maintain all intellectual property rights in and to the Lego® Serious Play® methodology as well as Lego® Serious Play® materials.

You can learn more about a person in an hour of play than you can from a lifetime of conversation" – Plato

description:

description:
Wolfram Meetups is a new initiative from Wolfram Research Europe committed to building a supportive, forward-thinking community of users discussing and facilitating best practice with Wolfram technologies. 

As a Wolfram Technology user, you have the knowledge, skills and ideas needed to do great things with Mathematica, SystemModeler and the Wolfram Language. 

Maybe you have questions about how you can improve your skills? Or perhaps you need a little nudge in the right direction to help you implement your next great idea? 

Join us today and attend our exclusive events to share with other users and learn from Wolfram’s technical minds.


Did you know?

We're on Twitter - @wolframresearch

And LinkedIn - search "Wolfram Research‎"

description:
Join the Belfast Puppet User Group (PUG) to gather with other Puppet users, and hear talks on Puppet, Configuration Management, and DevOps!

Puppet is IT automation software that helps system administrators manage infrastructure throughout its lifecycle, from provisioning and configuration to patch management and compliance. Using Puppet, you can easily automate repetitive tasks, quickly deploy critical applications, and proactively manage change, scaling from 10s of servers to 1000s, on-premise or in the cloud.

All participants are expected to follow Puppet Labs' code of conduct: bit.ly/eventconduct

description:
If you've ever visited Hacker News, you've almost certainly seen the "Show HN" or "Ask HN" posts. Well, it's time to get off the Internet and tell us about it face to face. We'll provide you with our honest feedback, you provide us with a great hack, or idea. 

We'll give you 5 minutes to show off your tool, hack, library (did you just write a library to access the Meetup API in Go!?), whatever. We're language and software/hardware agnostic, so it's all fair game. 

After you present, it's an open forum. The audience will ask questions and provide feedback. We want to enable as much participation as possible at these meetups, so you'd better be able to take criticism and dish it out (all within reason of course). N.B. personal projects only, no idea or startup pitching, no commercial plugs!

We're the newly formed London chapter of the multi-city Hack && Tell meetup movement. Show us some love by becoming a member and following us on Twitter (@hackandtellLDN).

description:
This group is for anyone interested in IT Security: [white, black) hat hackers, penetration testers, software developers, hardware hackers, network engineers, and anyone {passionate|curious} about (legitimately) breaking and defending IT systems. We aim to have short, technical, informal talks/demos where everyone can share ideas, present something interesting and learn new things.

A hackers meetup organised by the community and for community.

Each member has a great mind and is a source of intellectual capital, so the goal is to bring these brilliant minds together to have fun, share and learn from each other in informal and easy-going gatherings.

Join us to meet an excellent mix of passionate and competent hackers.

Get Involved

We aim to invite talented speakers who are looking to give back to the community and to interact with the members.

Ideas to improve our events are very welcome; if there are topics you want to hear about, please shoot us a message.

We’re on the lookout for two enthusiastic Co-organisers - get in touch if you want to contribute and have fun.

The rules:

The rules are simple: 

• RSVP to attend an event. Change your status if you can’t attend.

• Keep it cool and be respectful to other group members.


Thank you and see you soon!

description:
In the Century of Measurement, IoT is a new disruptive technology, with the potential of creating vast amounts of data, posing the questions are we measuring anything of value? A new strand of thinking is emerging asking how do we measure what matters ? Benefit realisation strategy is increasingly being used to predict where to look for new value and real intelligent change.

Surprisingly ? .. Not 'everything' is 'occurring' in the 'old smoke' there is intelligent life form 'North' of 'Tottenham Court Road' .. Therefore I would like to invite all Mid-Landers (well at least one significant other)  i.e Business Intelligence, Data Scientist, Data Managers, Data Analyst, Data Miners, Data visualizers .. etc etc  To please stand up, stand out ? or at least press the red button while 'minding the gap' and hopefully, one day, make  your way to a 'Data Hood' event. Where upon you can relax and be merry around camp-fires of shared and complimentary competences  at what could be 'predicted' as the 'real time' 'major' DATA adventures of Middle England.

description:
You’ve been thinking about becoming an entrepreneur for a while now and have a great idea for a startup, but aren’t quite sure whether it is viable, whether it will make you money, and where you should start? 

Let us help you out at our monthly MBJ TECHTALKS meetup for startuppers and social entrepreneurs, during which our consultants and senior level consultants will individually engage with you to turn your idea into a profitable business by helping you develop your idea in a purposeful manner and by giving you constructive, practical advice. 

Additionally, through presenting your idea to fellow attendees, you can get fruitful insights from others in your situation, be inspired by a creative crowd, and practice your pitch in a safe environment.The MBJ Meetups provide you with an excellent opportunity to meet like-minded entrepreneurs and to take your idea to the next level.

 Please note that places are limited and that MBJ employees and attendees are bound to confidentiality by a non-disclosure agreement to protect your intellectual property. We would also like to point out that as we can only accommodate a limited number of participants, we would greatly appreciate it if you would keep your RSVP status up to date.

description:
As Developers we are the linchpins of modern companies. It is time we had our own community to share ideas, learn together and build relationships with the people we need to create opportunities for ourselves.

So what do we do here...

Host Developer Meetups, attracting expert developers worldwide.

Co-working days to bring developers together.

Project space for end-to-end development and the creation of powerful teams.

Workshops, professional training and study jams to help broaden and deepen skills.

Develop for Startups to create technologically sound new businesses.

Develop for good, working with charities, not for profits and social enterprises.

...and hang-out together, have fun and do cool stuff!

If you have an event you'd like to make happen, something you'd like to learn, or something you'd like to get a group together to achieve, we'll work with you to make it happen.

Four initiatives we want your help to make happen...

Future Developer

Developer is not a recognised qualification - many leave education unaware it is a career. We aim to bring students and professional developers together, through shared coding, mentoring and work experience, to help build understanding and raise the profile of Developers and their role in modern organisations.

Develop the Developer

Many developers train on only one programming language or stage (front-end, back-end etc.). They're stuck, unable to migrate to newer languages or widen their skills. Structured programmes for widening/ deepening knowledge and skill will help developers find opportunities to cross-train, upskill and update.

Developing Business

Most startups have a good idea, but need technical help to turn it into a product, service and business. Meanwhile many developers have limited skills in business. We aim to put the two together - startups release the power of their idea through technology, developers learn how to create their own businesses.

Develop for Good

DataScience can connect people, make resources go further and solve many world problems. Developers transform effectiveness and capability of not for profit organisations, just as much as businesses.
We aim to focus the power of development and DataScience on social good, both at home and abroad.

description:
Agile is a time boxed, iterative approach to product development in which the product is built incrementally from the start of the project, instead of trying to deliver it all at once near the end.  

Why Agile 101?

Agile adoption is on the rise and as a result the need for skilled Agile practitioners is very high. Unfortunately, most people can’t justify the cost of a professional course to their employers so they are forced to read a few books or even worse, they just "wing it" and say they are "doing Agile". 

You cannot "do Agile" but you can definitely "become Agile" over time with the right foundation and lots of practice. Professional courses and books are a good start but are not enough. 

Our Aim

To really be Agile you need to understand the Agile values and principles. Our  aim is to help bridge the Agile knowledge gap .

We welcome everyone who wants to really understand the values and principles of Agile and also get an overview of the most popular methodologies (Scrum, XP, Lean and Kanban, etc). 

Our events will be interactive and experiential with  lots of audience participation to guarantee you learn something new each time and also have lots of fun in the process.

Want to host a session? 

We are always looking for speakers to share their knowledge and passion for Agile with the community. If you want to speak or facilitate a workshop or host a session, please contact us.

Join us on our experiential journey of #AgileDiscovery. Follow us on Twitter

description:
How we learn is changing; it's becoming more personal, instant and focused. Technology is now part of our everyday lives both at school, work or home, there is no escaping it, we have to embrace it. Technology offers so much potential in our everyday lives and impacts on our behaviour in school, work and play. Alone we can only scratch the surface of the potential, together we can explore it to its full potential.

There are some amazing cloud services and apps available for use in the delivery and management of learning such as Eliademy, Zaption and Google Docs. There are also cool tools which are connecting services like LTI, Zapier and IFTTT so you can mash and hack and create a dynamic and unique learning journey. 

This is a group to explore these tools and services, learn about how they work, their potential and how they could be improved. This isn't a group purely for coders, nor is it a group purely for thinkers. It's for those that are ready to dig in, plug together, tweak, bend the rules and play.

Who should join?

You should have a passion for education and how its delivery and management can be enhanced through technology. This can be in any role, as a front-line teacher, a back office administrator or someone involved in creating the learning tools and services.

What are the objectives of the group?

We want to explore the products and services that are available, demonstrate that they bring value to the learning process and share these with the wider community.

We want to generate ideas and creative approaches on how services could be hacked, mashed or tweaked to enhance education.

What will we do in the meetups?

The style and approach taken for each session will vary from the formal to the informal. But at the core it will be an opportunity to share and learn.

Why do this?

Technological take-up in education is still a subversive activity, held back by the practicalities of learning and access to the kit. More trainers are gaining access to computer technology and the introduction of the tablet has been a fundamental enabler, but  it's hard to experiment as individuals when the students you are teaching have so much at stake. Also, there are so many tools and services out there that it's hard to find the time to explore. By coming together as a group, we can try, learn and share. We are not alone in having imagination, so let's not play and learn alone.

description:
Are you in the process of launching or have launched an idea? Are you looking to scale it, generate revenue and investment? Are you looking to activate across multiple media touch points?

If you have answered yes to any of the above then we are here to help you. As well as running comms consultancy Horizon, we can be found mentoring at Mass Challenge, and NatWest's Entrepreneurial Spark so we know just how stringent resources can be for many startups. We bring together the community to help you learn, accelerate and achieve in a friendly environment.

If you would like to speak, would like to attend a personalised masterclass, or have any other questions, then please get in touch. If you are unable to make it to the events then check out our book, The Seen Startup which guides you through the processes.

description:
Innovation in insurance is nothing new.  Fantastic novel solutions to help businesses and individuals have been created for centuries and new products are appearing every day.  However innovation in terms of technology, customer engagement, telematics, data capture & analysis and so on appears to be lagging other industries.

The London InsTech 'meetup' group allows innovators, entrepreneurs, investors and professionals from across the market to identify and meet like-minded thinkers who are keen to ensure we maximise the opportunities offered by technology.

If you believe come and share your ideas; if you don't then come anyway and tell us why InsTech/InsurTech can't follow where FinTech has led.

Sign up to our newsletter at instech.london

Follow us on @InsTech_London

Check out our Passle Feed at instech-meetup.passle.net 

Join our LinkedIn group here

description:
This group is directed towards people that are interested in learning  Python which i believe is an extremely valuable  and useful subject to learn. I created this group because I have a very strong urge to learn Programming  from a basic level and would love to meet people who share this desire. 

There are 9 topics in total that we will be covering , doing one topic in each session.

My aim in these sessions is  to ensure that  everyone attending   a session leaves feeling like they have learnt and understood  significantly more on the topic being covered that day regardless of their prior knowledge .

In each session a topic from the ones listed below will be covered starting from the first one.


1. Python Number and operations (data types)

2. Python Strings

3. Python Listings

4. Python Tuples

5. Python Dictionaries

6. Python if, if-else and nested if elif ( conditional statement)

7. Python for loop and while loop

8. Python function

9. Python reading and writing values

description:
“The dream of the last century was to own a home. The dream of this century will be to own a company. Working for somebody else is like being a renter for your whole life. In the twenty-first century, we’ll all aspire to own a much larger piece of our lives.” Chris Dixon

Most of us still approach startups with a 20th century mindset. Focus on the idea. And follow the X-factor/Pop Idol approach – "pick me and give me lots of money". 

It is a lot harder than that. As Gabriel Weinberg put it –

“Most startups don’t fail at building a product. They fail at acquiring customers”. 

Our three key facts…

GROWTH: You are building a company, not just a product. And at the core of every successful company is a revenue engine. One which brings in the money which funds everything else. Building Traction is your number one priority.

TECHNOLOGY: Every company is now a technology company. If you aren’t using technology brilliantly so you can disrupt everyone else’s business model, someone else out there will do it against you. Building a technology platform is your key task - technology is everyone’s edge and the technology expert is now the best founder.

SPEED: Business plans used to change slowly - you could take your time building a new product. Now the average product life is under two years and organisations change their whole business model every decade. Your startup should come to life in months, not years, or your product will be out of date by the time you launch.

Growth | Technology | Speed

We have innovative plans to solve all three. Come and explore the options with us.

But we have three other ideas too

LEARN: Malcolm Gladwell outlined the 10,000 hour rule to gain a skill. We believe founders should practice and hone their skills in gaining traction, building revenue, handling technology and managing logistics before launching their big idea. We’re creating a school for founders to do just that.

COLLABORATE: Most founders struggle to find good co-founders. And find that they split the company into segments by doing so – a CTO, CSO etc., with a single point of failure for each. Virtual C is a modern mentoring system which gives founders the expertise they need, without tying up equity. People with experience and domain knowledge who come in as partners for the pitching stage, then step back when the company is ready to recruit the right people to drive it forward.

SHARE: Most good ideas never even reach startup stage as the founder doesn’t want to leave their job, hasn’t the skills etc. Many aren’t big enough to justify a separate startup, though they could be a profitable product for the right company. Probably 99% or more of ideas never happen. We funnel good ideas to people who can make them work, sharing profits equitably and making more people entrepreneurs.

Learn | Collaborate | Share

If you want to learn, have a good idea, or skills which can benefit a startup we want to hear from you.

And remember…

“If you don’t build your dream someone will hire you to help build theirs.”  Tony A. Gaskins Jr.

description:
I have set up a small group to tutor new users to computing, particularly tablets. Android to start with but can offer help to iPad users as well. The session will be in my home with no more than 4 people in a session. The level is basic - new starter.

If you have just bought a tablet or are thinking of buying one you will be welcome. It is intended to keep sessions to no more than two hours with a break if required.

There will be a small charge. Please contact me and let me know what you are looking to learn. Sessions are held weekly at 4pm - location close to Court Recreation Ground/Pound Lane. Numbers are limited to 4 but if warranted I can set up further sessions.

The aim of the group is to help people completely new to computing, particularly older people, to learn the basics of using computers on the Internet.

We'd like people, interested in helping silver surfers, to contact us. Help to spread the skills needed to access the internet. Need a venue big enough for 4-5 persons. Local libraries may offer an option.

description:
For all Periscopers and lovers of the Periscope app! We'll be getting together to discuss the best uses for the Periscope app, to highlight Periscopers of interest, and to learn from those who are putting this live streaming technology to market themselves and their businesses for social good or financial gain.

Who should join?

If you're an active user of the Periscope live streaming app, or are currently on the outside looking in, and are wondering how your personal or professional profile could benefit from becoming a Periscope user, you'll be welcome at our events.

Why you should join:

It can be tricky figuring out the best way to use a new platform or technology.  There are always those early adopters who "get it" straight away, grow their profile, and reap the benefits of a more visible online presence.  Our intention is to share those experiences and ideas, and to help the group collaborate in growing each other's profile on Periscope and beyond.

What can you expect?

A mix of networking over informal drinks, and some knowledge share.  We'll be having guest speakers who have "made it" on Periscope, and have them share their successes, how they did it, and suggest ways for our London Periscopers to make the app work for their own specific needs.

Still not sure what Periscope is?  Find out more here ... https://www.periscope.tv

description:
A group for people who put people first when they're designing public sector services. Service designers, user researchers, UX developers and anyone interested in how we make things better are welcome! 

It's an exciting time to be an advocate for users in public sector services. A lot of the detail around how we practice agile principles, especially with users is still forming. I want to collaborate with people like you (you've read this far ;P) towards a set of best user experience practices in the public sector.

I want to actively think and discuss three broad areas:

 1. how we learn about the users of public services

 2. how we present and integrate that knowledge with developers and 'product owners' in an agile way

 3. common problems that we face as user advocates in public services. 

This group will be an open safe space, with lots of discussion, and creativity. Together we will actively contribute to making public services more user focused. 

When: 6.30pm, last Tuesday of every month

Where: In a pub in London

Session structure: 1. hellos 2. two speakers have 10 mins each to present an idea, learning, experience, or problem to the group (finishes with three questions) 3. group discussion 4. drinks. 

*The lovely dxw are now sponsoring the event so there will be a good tab behind the bar!*

I'm super open to any ideas about the group or session. Talk to me @rosebotanic , #pb4pixels

Check out talks you missed on : www.slideshare.net/pb4pixels

description: Robots.IO presents a series of workshops that focus on learning through making, with digital fabrication at its core, through the use of IO robot simulation plug-in for Rhino’s Grasshopper . In these workshops, participants will engage in 3D printing using Robots.IO in-house robots, in order to generate their personal designs, which they can later keep. Participants will be introduced to robotic fabrication and will investigate approaches to generate forms through digital parametric design and physical prototyping. The fabrication process of this workshops will speculate on the advantages of using 6-axis robotic arms to extend what is possible in conventional 3D printing. Robotic control and material intelligence will be combined to allow a new way of free-form 3D printing. This workshop is appropriate for professionals and students. For more information, check: http://robots.io/wp/portfolio/robotic-3d-printing-workshops-may-2015

description:
OpenStack is a free and open-source cloud computing software platform.  Users primarily deploy it as an infrastructure as a service (IaaS) solution.  It began in 2010 as a joint project of Rackspace Hosting and NASA. Then OpenStack Foundation, a non-profit corporate entity, was established to promote OpenStack software and its community.  More and more companies have joined the project and the technology is making inroads into the enterprise.

We aim to promote the recent development within this area and organise meetups with the members. We will also invite overseas speakers to do presentations for the community.

description:
DPM Bournemouth is brought to you by John Luke Le Page and Dan Tarrant, with the aim of creating a local community of Digital Project Management professionals in Bournemouth. Meetups occur on the second Thursday of every month and consist of various discussions and talks. The floor is always open for impromptu presentations on anything Project Management if you’re willing to share your own experiences.

Whether you’re a Junior or Senior in the management of digital projects, or even looking to break into Project Management, our meetups are all inclusive and range in topics. We’re a small group of professionals who are happy to share their knowledge and experiences.  So if you have anything you'd like to discuss or learn, then come along to one of our meetups to mix with like minded professionals.

description:
You and I know the future of financial services is not the banks. So why is every 'FinTech' meetup in London aimed at, sold to and paid for by the banks? 

This is a meetup designed to encourage community in the progressive London FinTech scene. Let's get people talking about how to solve key problems in this space, over a beer (oh yeah, there'll be beer). 

For each meetup we'll host three folk from FinTech companies to talk for 10-15 minutes (tops!). Talks should cover two things: (1) outline a specific problem the company is having (or one faced by users), and (2) explain how the team is trying to tackle it (hence 'one job'!). 

If you'd like to sponsor an event or have a cool idea for a talk, get in touch with me at bkursar@gmail.com or on Twitter (@baileytalks).

Sign up for email updates: eepurl.com/bj9rxr

I'd like to meet like minded people/techies interested in volunteering their skills, passion and a little time to build new technologies, services and solutions that solve social problems like... helping unemployed school leavers get practical experience in a particular career or creating software and support programmes that enable isolated old folk to connect with family, friends... anyone. Probs could be local/global, whatever we think most worthy.

If you have a skill (especially, but not limited to): dev, test, web design, SEO, servers, stack, architecture, whatever you do... And you want to help, join the group and contact me with list of those skills and any ideas you have for projects.

This is about people collaborating to build technology that makes the world a better, safer and more inclusive place. OK Bristol, let's see if there's anyone out there as deluded as I am. First member gets a jammy dodger.

description:
Imaging Mind is a futurist agency and visual culture community dedicated to uncovering the future of imaging and how it manifests itself in technology and society. We want to accelerate innovation in the visual space by facilitating meaningful interactions between artists, creators, researchers, startups and corporates in an experiential and narrative driven platform. For this, we offer a narrative driven platform and related services, making sense out of contemporary developments in visual culture, entrepreneurship, exponential technology and design, focused around the future of imaging. 

About Future Vision Meetups

Imaging Mind, in co-operation with The Photographers Gallery, presents the London Future Vision series of meetups that explores visual culture and imaging at the intersection of culture and technology. Every month, we'll dive into a specific topic from a visual perspective and look at the cultural influence of the topic in usage, technology, business and art. We’ll have guest speakers, a travelling hardware lab and plenty of opportunity to meet likeminded people and exchange thoughts. Want to suggest a theme for a future vision meetup? Let us know!

About Hack The Visual

Our Hack The Visual events focus on envisioning, prototyping, testing and experiencing new imaging technologies. ANYONE WITH A PASSION FOR VISUALS, regardless of whether that stems from a technology or an art perspective is welcome. If you can CREATE, DESIGN, PROGRAM, or FEEL VISUALS, we encourage you to join our HACK THE VISUAL meetups and hackathons.

description:
A meetup group for people interested in helping the open data movement grow in Wales. We particularly welcome developers, data wranglers, journalists, civil servants, visualisation people, storytellers, hackers, open source enthusiasts. You don't have to fit any of those descriptions, if you have an interest in open data and you're willing to contribute, you're welcome.

Rather than just be a conversational group we like to have a bias toward action. Be prepared to be invited to contribute your skills to any projects that come up. You are also welcome to propose projects. If you do so you should be willing to take responsibility for driving the project forward.

description:
The Flag & Bell (F.A.B) is a monthly mini pub crawl for techies and entrepreneurs. 

This is the Bath version of the successful London group started in 2006. Once a month, on the first Wednesday of the month, the group visit a couple of pub/bars/venues/events in Bath.

FAB meetings are friendly, fun and rewarding. It's an opportunity to chat about the latest developments in web/mobile/cloud tech and start ups. You'll learn about new places, people and ideas and make friends and business connections. 

Just listen for the bell and follow the flag!

description:
The Application of the Internet of Things (IoT) has now come a long way from the story of the Coke machine at Carnegie Melon University in 1980s.  From the initial Machine-to- Machine (M2M) capabilities used in manufacturing, power and utilities, the “Thing” now can be any natural or man-made object that can be assigned an IP address.  More objects are becoming embedded with sensors and gaining the ability to communicate. The resulting information networks promise to create new business models and improve business processes.

So every company, irrespective of their size, involved with ICT (Information and Communication Technology) service infrastructure believes that they have a pivotal role to play in the Internet of Things.  So now is the time to understand the evolving value chain and find out your place here.

We aim to promote the recent development within this area and organise meetups with the members. We will also invite overseas speakers to do presentations for the community.

description:
UX Crunch 

For more information follow us on twitter @theuxcrunch or check out our website www.theuxcrunch.co.uk


The UX Crunch is London’s largest user experience, networking events and conferences monthly. User experience is one of the hottest debatable subjects within the digital world with networking and learning key to UX professionals keen to develop their careers.In a contract-heavy market, it’s always great to network with hiring managers and meet potential connections that could help you secure your next contract.  We approach creating networking events in a unique way, showcasing various companies’ user experience and knowledge by hosting our events at various venues around London. We aim to create a new phenomenon within digital networking, making cutting edge events and opening possibilities of collaboration within the UX community.


Our events often offer free drinks and food as well as some of the most inspirational user experience guest speakers in the industry. We welcome people who are looking to get in UX and find out more about the area. Recruiters and hiring managers are also welcome and we encourage jobs and opportunity networking in an ever-changing and evolving industry.  


Host an event 


We are always looking for major companies to host events. Hosting is free, however you will be expected to provide food and drink for the attendees as well as a space large enough to hold more than 60 people. 

Hosting an event is a great way of getting exposure to a huge user experience audience. This helps promote your brand name, encourages people to join your organisation and gives you a great way of promoting to your clients/customers. Those hosting the UX Crunch can promote the event on their social media platforms to demonstrate support for the UX community and you take pride in your website’s usability. For more information, contact info@digitalshowcase.com 


Sponsor UX Crunch 


UX Crunch is Europe’s largest monthly UX meet-up with hundreds of user experience professionals attending each month, Why not become a partner and be seen by over 1000 UX attendees across networking events throughout the year. We are looking for three sponsors for 2016 to partner us in our events. 


Why Sponsor us? 


 Generate new leads

 Build brand presence and raise profile in the UX community 

 Forge strategic partnerships and joint ventures

 Support the UX community 

 Network with industry people  

 Use us in your sales pitches to client’s, candidates and via your marketing info


What you will get as part of the package:


 Overall sponsorship of the event, with a particular focus on keynote sessions.

 Branding throughout pre-publicity across all communications channels (website and email communications), plus high visibility during the event in networking areas, event screens, agenda, attendee packs.

 Recognition at opening and closing of each event by presenter.

 Advertise your brand within the event using banners  

 Have your name included on our website and meet-up groups 

 Have you name printed on all our name badges 

 Post jobs on our UX Crunch website 

 Gain free sponsor tickets to all our events and offer them to your staff, candidates and clients

description:
Free Introductory Courses for professionals, entrepreneurs, business owners who wants to boost their business or improve their earnings, and make a difference in the world.

Ever wondered how people build websites like Twitter, Facebook, Kickstarter and Meetup? Is it possible for someone with no programming experience? What do you learn and what do you do?

This evening course is a short, non-technical guide to how to build websites and apps. Jargon-free and easy to understand, but full of important information. I've lived and run tech startups for the past 2 years. I'm going to teach you everything I can in a short, evening session - broken down into a way that makes sense for absolutely anyone, even complete beginners.

The evening will cover:

• How these apps and websites work on the inside

• How you can build the site, like Kickstarter, Twitter, Facebook, the Yellow Pages.

• Why you should and shouldn't learn these skills

• Exactly which programming languages that are worth learning, that you can use to build a killer portfolio of functioning, profit-generating websites.

• Where to learn them for FREE

• Why startups are so valuable right now

• Why your unlocked talent is in demand - the £40k - £80k jobs available & exactly how to get them, down to the exact emails I have used.

• The exact tools I use.

• Where I go for information

• How I can solve any programming problem with 3 approaches.

• Exactly what to read and watch to teach yourself - at your own speed - everything you need.

I want you to be able to design and build... from scratch... websites and apps that solve real-world problems.


I hope to see you at our next event! Any questions or thoughts, please don't hesitate to get in contact.

Best,

Will


p.s. Being able to create these sites, from nothing, doesn’t require a team or thousands of pounds. One person can do it on a budget of zero. That's why I've created this meetup, and why I think it can be so powerful in changing people's lives.

description:
Digital freelancers: the Big Brains for Small Business group was set up to generate a conversation in the digital industry about how to direct some of our talent and skills towards paid small business projects, without compromising too much (I know, it's not easy).

We need to talk about how we can help small businesses compete, otherwise they won't survive the digital age! (plus, we'll get a more fulfilling, varied career experience).

This group is for you if you tend to work on big project for agencies or large enterprises, but wish there was a way to combine that type of work with smaller (paid) projects where you can make a HUGE IMPACT.

Let's get to know others like us in a relaxed space, share stories, generate ideas and conversations and who knows, perhaps collaborations and new methodologies!

description: Large Scale Scrum (LeSS) is to the organisation what Scrum is to the team; an simple, powerful, large-scale product development framework designed to evolve into something that fits perfectly with any unique context. It has been created by Craig Larman and Bas Vodde and you can read more at the http://less.works site. This meetup is allow those interested in, certified in, or practicing LeSS to meet, learn, train and co-operate to make LeSS better and guide its adoption in our organisations.   You are also encouraged to join the London Scrum User Group, where other related topics are discussed.

description:
OpenCart, Realex Payments and Welford Media will be hosting a series of Meetup's dedicated to OpenCart developers and merchants in London, UK. Completely free of charge, these OpenCart Meetup's and training sessions will give OpenCart enthusiasts the unique chance to learn about the latest additions to the OpenCart system from developers who helped to design and build them. 


We ran the first OpenCart Meetup on the 12th of February which covered: 

• In-depth technical overview of OpenCart 2.0 

• Extended Q&A session with the OpenCart Team 

• One-on-one training opportunities 

• Networking opportunities with other developers 

• Free food and beer! 


The next session will be on the 11th of June and the agenda is as follows: 

• Great networking opportunities 

• Free food and beer! 

• How you can keep on top of your store’s SEO 

• What you can do to increase your online presence 

• Relaxed workshop giving you the chance to get hands-on advice 

• One-on-one training opportunities 

Sign-up quick because places are limited and do run out!

description:
This group is open to software professionals, entrepreneurs, academics, enthusiasts, makers/hobbyists, and early-adopters. Topics covered include: M2M, Artificial Intelligence, Drones (UAVs), Self-Sriving Vehicles, Machine Vision, Wearables (Virtual Reality, Augmented Reality, Fitness Trackers, Smartwatches), Intelligent Transportation Systems (ITS), Industrial Asset Control & Monitoring, Smart Home, Smart City, Big Data, Robotics, Machine Learning, Autonomous Transport, Maker/Hacker products (Arduino, Raspberry Pi, Intel Edison) etc. 

IoT will transform the way we live and work. Connected sensors embedded within all kinds of objects will make the world around us smarter, safer, and more energy efficient. The IoT revolution is happening now, so join us!

description:
This is a group based in London for anyone interested in the legal principles applicable to digital property rights and the business models associated with cloud computing. Depending on interest, the meetups could include talks and workshops about recent developments in the field, or just friendly conversation.

The group is aimed at legal and other professionals involved in advising clients about the administration of the property rights associated with digital information and digital asset management. Proprietors of businesses using or providing cloud services could also find the discussions useful in the conduct of their businesses. Finally, trustees, personal representatives, court of protection deputies and other fiduciaries using cloud services would benefit from involvement in the discussions of the group.

description:
Want to talk and learn more about Lean and Agile but can't get to a meetup?

You can find all the information you need to join us on our meetup About Page.

If you are in London then do check-out the London Lean Coffee meetup group. You'll find many other Lean Coffee[tm] groups all around the country.

description:
Platform as a Service (PaaS) is the here and now for devops focused cloud native apps. Pivotal Cloud Foundry is the core technology behind many popular PaaS solutions on the market from IBM, HP etc. This user group brings together people who are involved, using or want to know about Cloud Foundry and other agile technology from Pivotal.  

This is a group for anyone interested in a more agile approach to developing, deploying, managing and updating the innovative new cloud-native applications which modern businesses needs to survive and thrive. 

People should join this group if they write application code or manage/run/work in IT operations that use or may want to use Cloud Foundry. Its a chance to hear latest news and trends, share stories, learn with hands on experience and network with other Pivotal users. We aim to  have regular meet-ups focusing on specific industries. you can expect to attend hands-on workshops, seminars and talks from Cloud Foundry users and developers.

description: This is a group for anyone interested in big data, DISTRIBUTED COMPUTING and FUNCTIONAL PROGRAMMING (DIS-FUNCTIONAL). You see the challenges that come from offering a complete streaming solution for businesses. Libraries such as akka-stream and scalaz-stream provide compositional API's for processing streams on single nodes, while Apache Spark Streaming provides a multi-node solution for (mini-batched) stream processing. Moroever, Apache Kafka is a scalable solution for getting all those precious streams safely on and off disk. If this sounds interesting, stick around.

This is a group to connect fashion, technology and science, to explore meaningful engagement of technology. Calling for fashion designers, textile innovators, developers, coders, makers, electronic engineers, scientists, sociologists and anyone who are interested to sit and hack together. While the fashion tech now have a focus on commerciality this group is open for hacking and debate on fashion in a broader sense, from philosophy, system to social applications and making. The aim is to merge the creative and tech community. The group aims to meet twice a month and host two major Hackathons with Showcase every year. At the starting up stage of the group, anyone who has a project can post their ideas to find collaborators. Whenever we have at least one project we will announce the meet and hack! Couldn't wait to see what comes out of the other end!

Twitter: @FashHackLondon

description:
Welcome to SEO Manchester Meetup group! As you have probably guessed, this group is about SEO (search engine optimisation), and pretty much anything and everything to do with internet marketing. - PPc

- Gig Economies

- Marketing & Sales

- E-Commerce

- Social Media Marketing

We will soon have an entire online platform with all of these things broken down too. Look forward to having you on board!

description:
Come join our friendly IoT meetup group in Brighton. We aim to cover the full spectrum of topics, from Technology through to FinTech.

Some of the topics we will cover are: - IoT and Cloud - Embedded systems (including open source hardware such as Raspberry Pi ; Arduino) - Wireless & Telecoms ; Sensor networks - IoT ; Big Data - Legal & Security aspects - Business impact of IoT - Financing your IoT project

But this group isn't just for geeks. We need to build a vibrant IoT community here in Brighton. So we welcome Entrepreneurs, Creative / Artistic people, Finance people, Policy makers. In fact, if you are in any way curious about how this technology will shape the future, then this group is for you.

We will invite guest speakers on specialist topics. And if you have a project you wish to showcase, then you are more than welcome to bring it along and get some feedback from your fellow group members.

We will look at the kind of IoT projects that are going on in the UK and throughout the world and envision how we can create the Brighton of the future. Sounds interesting? Sign up now and be part of the next great wave of digital innovation in Brighton!

description:
Founded in New Zealand in 2014, CodeSmashers run workshops that teach you how to design & develop beautiful websites. 

We are going worldwide and London is our first stop! 

Our project-based style of learning begins with an intensive 2-day workshop. You don’t need any previous knowledge or experience of web design to come along, but we can guarantee you will walk out inspired and ready to get started on your own projects. 

We will teach you the skills to build your own beautiful website using HTML, CSS and the Bootstrap framework that looks great on mobile devices. 

During and following the workshop, you receive exclusive access to our collaborative online platform HackSpace where you can share ideas with fellow students while receiving ongoing support from our tutors. 

With CodeSmashers, learning code can be fun.

Check out our website: www.codesmashers.co/uk , like us on www.facebook.com/codesmashers or follow us on www.twitter.com/codesmashers

description:
Welcome to the Milton Keynes DevOps meetup!

This is a community for those interested in learning and sharing DevOps practice and experience in Milton Keynes.

If you are a DevOps Engineer, a Systems Administrator, or Software Developer building or running web/cloud services (or just interested!) in Milton Keynes then this group is for you!

We are passionate IT professionals who are doing 'DevOps' day to day and are interested in meeting like minded individuals to share and exchange knowledge locally.

Our (ongoing) journey has been long and eventful and we are keen to help others along the road and learn from the wider sphere of DevOps experience, what's hot and what's not, what works, and what doesn't.


Our evenings will comprise of 2 to 3 short talks on a range of DevOps related subjects. We will aim to approach the topics from both Dev and Ops perspectives, discussing tools, practice, and culture. 

Following the talks there will be food and drink, and a chance to socialise with one another.

description:
Welcome!

We like to hack, learn, share, socialise and have fun while using AngularJS. Neither talks, nor slides, nor workshops. Only you hacking alone or in pairs in our sessions. We give you everything so you can try new things for yourself without the hassle.

All experience levels and backgrounds are welcome. 

AngularJS Labs Sessions

Sessions are limited to 15 people. Laptop is not mandatory but recommended. 

Topics

Expect a lot of AngularJS goodness and the usual suspects: Angular 1.x/2, Testing, Performance, Good practices, and lots of JavaScript!

description:
SQLMidlands - Bringing the West Midlands SQL Server community together.

WHAT?

We normally hold meetings every other month, usually on a Thursday after work in the centre of Birmingham. It's an informal gathering of like minded people, with a couple of speakers presenting hour long sessions including tips, techniques and information on old, new and upcoming technology.

We like to get a mixture of world leading speakers as well as providing an opportunity for our members to present. We tailor the speakers and sessions to your requests so if you have any specific topics that you want to go through, then come along and let us know. Each meetup consists of two speakers presenting topics for an hour each, with a break in the middle for some food and networking.

We're part of the UK SQL Server community at www.sqlserverfaq.com and we're an official PASS chapter (the Professional Association for SQL Server) covering the Midlands in the UK.

We also use Eventbrite, so feel free to sign up to whichever platform you prefer. 

WHERE?

MAC Birmingham (Midlands Art Centre), opposite Edgbaston Cricket Ground, B12 9QH

In the Pincent Masons 1 room upstairs above the entrance. 

Free parking on site.

WHEN?

The 2nd or 3rd Thursday of odd months (Jan, March, May, July, Sept, Nov)

The first session starts at 6:30pm, second session finishes at 9pm.

ANYTHING ELSE?

Dress code: Casual

Food: Light snacks provided (usually sandwiches and chips)

Size: Usually between 20 and 40 people

description:
This is a group for all-things Citrix Hosted Desktops, where Citrix Service Providers can learn how to grow their Service Provider Business. We are a community of business professionals and technicians who meet and share ideas as a Mastermind and learn what others are doing and succeeding with in the CSP Programme in delivering Hosted Desktops (DaaS). Leading figures from the community share their stories, their victories and the ones that got away.  The aim of the CSP User Group is to get local partners together regularly to talk about your experiences, successes, and difficulties with your clients and prospects and to use the mastermind and networking principals to be a resource for technical and business professionals who want to keep pace with the Desktop as a Service arena and related Cloud and Virtualisation technologies. We will aim to have at least one CSP partner or Citrix to present a Success Story, a War Story and updates of course on the business and market trends. We will invite technology partners to speak and include related organisations such as Microsoft, AWS, and other public cloud providers to share their stories too. With 2700 CSP partners worldwide, what matters is that you're talking about Desktop as a Service (DaaS) and related topics that are interesting and important to you. This is not a sales pitch, this is an information sharing and updating opportunity for the community to gather as they need and grow their businesses. The group will also present updates on other events organised by relevant groups, vendors and partners which can help you. We invite specialists and new technologies to present about innovative technology solutions. This group is also structured to enable participants to help each other with solution challenges if necessary. We will also drink some wine and beer and take a snack too. With already 500,000 Citrix CSP Hosted Desktops out there, this is the place to meet, learn and do more business. We are virtuosos because doing Virtual Desktops is an art!

For speaking and sponsorship requests please message via the app

description:
Meet other developers and ops engineers using Docker. Docker is an open platform for developers and sysadmins to build, ship, and run distributed applications. Consisting of Docker Engine, a portable, lightweight runtime and packaging tool, and Docker Hub, a cloud service for sharing applications and automating workflows, Docker enables apps to be quickly assembled from components and eliminates the friction between development, QA, and production environments. As a result, IT can ship faster and run the same app, unchanged, on laptops, data center VMs, and any cloud.

Learn more about Docker at http://www.docker.com

description:
Welcome to the third era of computing. Computer-based information processing  is now a practical reality that is ubiquitous and pervasive in so many things that we do today. Nevertheless the power of computing largely remains implicit, unappreciated and even misunderstood to the most.

We are at the dawn of Cognitive Computing. Where the power of information processing meets highly adaptive cognitive algorithms and vast data sets and sensor inputs about all aspects of our lives. The destiny is limited by our capacity to imagine and harness this vast potential underneath man-machine-data interaction.

In this meet up, we will discuss about the trends in computing; around predictive analytics, machine learning techniques that utilizes large and disparate data sets and about emerging platforms that support all these, for example, IBM Bluemix. And we will roll up our sleeves and start working on some practical examples and contribute to the community.

description:
We're a group of mobile app developers (iOS and Android), mobile startups, and mobile marketers interested in growing our apps. From organic growth hacking, to paid installs, to deep links and referral systems, we cover all things related to growth. Come hang out with us, listen to some great speakers, and learn from some incredible mobile growth experts. 

Stay up to date with the latest mobile growth tips:

Join us on Facebook | Sign up for the blog | Check out videos from our past events

Mobile Growth Meetups are powered by Branch and Grow.Co.

Branch provides free deep linking technology to mobile app developers and marketers. We're on a mission to help you grow their business through deep linking, and allow users to discover content inside mobile apps. In 14 months Branch grew to a company with 50 employees and raised 18 million in funding. In the last year, Branch has gone from powering deep linking for 6 million users to more than 1 billion users.

Grow.co is a community of growth marketing professionals and brands, comprised of more than 7,000 acquisition and retention-oriented professionals. We serve the community through industry summits, a weekly newsletter, a jobs board, and an online forum.

description:
Love technology? Love fundraising? Want to gossip about queries, website integrations or users who ask you for too many favours? Want to brag about your new widget or learn about innovation in our not-for-profit sector? Then come to … Tech 3rd THIRSTday! 

The IoF Tech Group have distilled the networking element of our events and created a monthly meet-up. IOFT3T is held at a central London pub on the third Thursday of every month, and is a networking meeting for those who want to meet other people interested in databases, donation forms and everything in-between! 

This is a free event, with your first drink on us. The fun doesn’t end there, because at IoFT3T we have… The #UnDebate In a mash-up UnConference and a debate, a #UnDebate is where we’ll generate a debate topic on the night, and two volunteers will compete in speed debates for an iconic award. Expect intellectual genius moments and some “bantz”! Whether you are from a large organisation or small, or whether you want to UnDebate or watch, come join us! 

More information about our voluntary group is here: http://www.ioftech.org.uk

description:
The original and first meetup for digital professionals is back!

Started in 2004, digital playground was the first meetup that was created in London for digital professionals. It had over 100 digital pioneers meeting monthly in London for its regular socials. 

What is digital playground?

digital playground is founded on monthly meetups that are informal social events giving you the chance to let your hair down (if you have some) and mingle with like-minded people. More informative events are co-ordinated in between the monthly socials which include talks, seminars and workshops, hosted by some of the industry's top bods. We will also cross-promote any other interesting digital events going on in London so you won't miss out on anything essential.

Who should join?

All prospective members are vetted and must be currently practicing in a digital job role. Whether you are client side, agency side or part of a digital service/product, you are invited to join if you are in digital advertising, marketing, creative, production or operational roles. All member details are only shared with other members and are kept private from public view. 

When is this starting?

We are intending to start with our monthly social events as soon as membership reaches 100. We will be acquiring sponsorship for the event location and free bar so please sign up now and we will be in touch when we are ready to launch with our first event. Once the informal socials are up and running we will start to introduce the informative events. We will also be intending to run one large yearly summer event next year and will have a national awards ceremony from Jan 2017.

How to get approved?

Please make sure you fill out your full profile with either your linkedin or twitter account details. If you have neither then message some other evidence to one of the meetup organisers. We must have evidence that you are currently in a digital role otherwise we must decline membership.

.....and on that note please don't apply if you're not in the digital roles we have suggested! Other areas of design such as interior, architecture or roles in traditional media such as non-digital broadcasting, publishing or music do not qualify. Also we want to make is crystal clear that if you're a non-digital supplier to digital industries such as life-coaching, recruitment agencies, procurement savers etc you will also be declined.

The last thing which is more optional than necessary but is for your own benefit is to upload a real picture of yourself. Avatars or illustrations make it difficult to put a face to a name. Please also log back in once registered and complete your profile introduction. 

Thanks and we look forward to meeting you :)

description:
Medidata Solutions is the leading global provider of cloud based solutions for clinical trials. We are a forward thinking company always looking to develop and innovate.

This will be an ongoing networking opportunity for likeminded people in the tech world. If you would like to attend please confirm your attendance.

description:
The pressures facing species and ecosystems across the planet demand a radical change in conservation solutions.

Smart Earth Network is a new social enterprise whose aim is to create a framework within which conservationists, technologists and entrepreneurs can collaborate, fund and develop solutions for conservation.

The focus is on two areas:

The enhancement of systems for the monitoring, evaluation, decision-making and action related to conservation biodiversity.

The proving of claims made by environmentally accredited products and services.

This Meetup is one of the activities of the Smart Earth Network, providing a forum for conservationists and technologists to share experiences and ideas and discuss how best to develop the network.

Get involved and please signup as member of our network!

description:
Are you a Bristol & Bath Alumni? Do you come from the region, did you go to school/university there, or do you simply have a love for it and are interested in knowing more about what’s going on in the biggest digital cluster outside of London (in terms of number of jobs - TechNation report) and the ‘only fast growing and globally significant tech cluster in the UK’ according to McKinsey & Co? 

Not only do we think Bristol & Bath is one of the most amazing places in the UK, so does the Times (Bristol named best city to live in), and with the electrification of the Great Western Route extending to Bristol & Bath in 2018, the links with London are getting ever stronger.

This is a Meetup for those who work in tech and digital industries in London but wish to keep in touch with what’s going on in Tech in the West and to explore opportunities for them or their businesses.

The series of evening events will start in July and will be hosted by some of the most exciting companies that were founded in or have moved to this vibrant cluster.

description:
Digital DIY is a community for anyone starting a business or a personal project, keen to explore how to do-tech-yourself on a budget. All skills and levels are welcome! 

We'll meet once a week for sharing the latest non-techie digital resources, tools and digital tips & tricks on stuff like blogging, e-commerce, web design, digital marketing etc. The focus will be on bootstrapping, and how we can help each other do it yourself in the digital space, for free (or next to nothing!) - without hiring an array of tech experts, designers and develpers.
