description:
Are you a lady? Do you code? Are you searching for a similar bunch of ladies to discuss code with?

You’ve come to the right place. We meet monthly to hear talks from leaders in the field and hack whilst developing our code-fu in the process.

What if I don’t code?

We are going to be discussing some pretty in-depth, geeky stuff. If you are not deterred by that and are still really excited about coming, you’re more than welcome. If you’re looking for a good place to learn to code, that’s excellent news! There are some brilliant meetups where you can work with other people who are getting started. Message us and we'll point you in the right direction.

Do I have to be a lady?

If you consider yourself to be a lady, we do too. If you identify as non-binary, you are more than welcome to attend. We look forward to seeing you soon.

description:
Hands-on training of how to develop IoT apps using LwM2M for IoT Developers who would like experience with standardized protocols and the sponsoring HW platform. We will be providing the HW boards and an FAE to train people how to use the boards.  

Who Should Attend

ØMakers 

 •In the market there are several platforms that can host and support OMA LwM2M protocol 

 •At the workshop you will learn how to install the software in one of these platforms, expose sensor information to a Server running in a sandbox and create your own set of sensors and values. 

ØDevelopers 

 •Eclipse Foundation is developing two LwM2M projects: •Wakaama – C language •Leshan – Java

•You can contribute and enhance these projects or construct your own applications and services around this protocol. 

 ØRobotic Enthusiasts 

 •OMA LwM2M protocol can be used in a wide range of situations, where you need to expose sensor values to a cloud server. The protocol will allow you to establish the communication to read, write and execute functions in the Client.

About OMA and LwM2M

Open Mobile Alliance, (OMA), is a non-profit International Development Standards Organization

based in San Diego, California, United States. Our members go from small to blue-chip companies who are committed to create interoperable Technical Specifications that set standards in the market. 

OMA  has developed a IoT protocol called OMA LightWeightM2M, (LwM2M). This protocol allows the communication between a Client and a Server. The LwM2M Client is installed in a hardware platform and exposes sensor information to a remote LwM2M Server. OMA has also constructed an OMA LwM2M Developer Toolkit to assist developer and makers in understanding an using these specifications.

description:
This is an invite only group for Directors who work in the Tech sector within South West Region of the UK. Absolutely no salespeople, lawyers, accountants or recruitment agents. We meet and socialise and chat about whatever is of interest to the group - how to hire techies in the region, government engagement, local enterprise investment, engaging between start up and mature tech companies in the region.

If you are a Director in the IT industry in the region and you haven't been invited - you may apply but your application will be reviewed before you are approved to join - this is to ensure the quality of the group and the meetups.  So please include your linkedin profile - if you don't and I can't easily find you on linkedin I will have to reject your application.

The group will meet at least once every two months and the goals for the group will be decided by it's members.  There will be no charge for admission, no advertising and no sponsorship, but also no free drinks or food to ensure an unbiased networking group.

description:
Glug is a series of events for the design and creative community.
Our showcase event is held in London but there are now 15 other events around the world.

Based around a series of talks and informal networking, Glug has become one of the most exciting, credible and well attended creative events around.

Established in 2007, it’s an eclectic mix of people from all creative walks of life; from advertising, graphic design and the visual arts through to fashion, architecture and the crafts.

It’s a fine melting pot indeed, regularly attended by creatives, students, clients, cultural voyeurs, hipsters and the industry elite. Come! Be intoxicated and inspired, you’re also bound to make some new contacts, friends and maybe even find that next job/contract/lover.

Be part of the movement.

—

Check the videos here www.vimeo.com/glug, our website www.glugevents.com, Twitter and Facebook.

Please note: Refunds will only be processed if the event is cancelled or moved to another date.

See you at the bar, 

Nick, Ian & Crew at Glug HQ 

—

Glug - Notworking™

www.twitter.com/glug

www.facebook.com/GlugNotworking

www.instagram.com/glugevents

www.glugevents.com

—

Please note we don't offer refunds, feel free to pass the tickets on amongst yourselves here on meetup and www.twitter.com/glug #glugtickets usually works a treat.

description:
On March 23 & 24 2016, taking place at the QEII Centre, in the heart of London, The London Bitcoin Forum is bringing together 900 attendees, more than 60 expert speakers and 20+ media partners for a prestigious two-day event featuring powerful keynote talks, plenty of networking opportunities, demos and panels about upcoming challenges and opportunities provided by Bitcoin and the Blockchain Technology in this new emerging reality where collaboration is the key.


Topic Table:

•  Meet the Blockchain Startups

•  The Future of Blockchain

•  Global and UK Regulation and Compliance Panel

•  Blockchain Investor Panel

•  Public Blockchains vs Private Blockchains Debate

•  Debate on Scaling Issues, Blocksize Limit and Forks

•  Financial Smart Contracts on the Blockchain

•  Distributed Ledger Technology

•  Bitcoin in the Gambling Industry

•  Career Opportunities with Blockchain Companies


Website: https://londonbitcoinforum.co.uk

Email: contact@londonbitcoinforum.co.uk

description: This is a group for anyone interested in Interactive Music, Experimental Music, new music formats and more. Everyone is welcome; whether you're an enthusiast, producer, artist, developer, or just curious. We're asking: - What's next for music? - Can listeners not just 'play', but 'play with' music? - Why should major services, like Spotify, dominate the distribution of recorded music? - How can we embrace the innovation surrounding us, to take music beyond its borders and conventions? - Which is your favourite four-legged creature and why? We'll be meeting up in London's venues, pubs, and co-working spaces to: - Showcase and discuss new technologies and interactive work; - Listen and Q&A with guest experts who will throw light on the subject; - Attend interactive music exhibitions; - Connect with like-minded people in the process. Join us to explore this form together. Looking forward to meeting you!

description:
Welcome to the Milton Keynes .NET user group. 

This is a group for anyone based around the three counties (Beds, Bucks and Herts) to meet up and talk about Microsoft .NET technologies. 

There are no firm plans for the group yet so I think it would be great to find out the level of interest people have on this, and then moving on to something more formal. Ideas are very welcomed here. If you work with .NET technologies or anything related, feel free to get in touch and suggest talks of around 20 minutes per slot. 

Would also be awesome to have some "Lightning Talks" of about 5 minutes each. Right now, it would also be great to get some suggestions of locations we can meet up. Ideally somewhere we can use on a regular basis to get the momentum going.

Twitter: @DotMiltonKeynes

description: This is a Meetup to explore exponential technologies - technologies that are on the exponential growth curve and that will impact us over the coming years, and indeed have already started to do so. description: This group is for anyone that would like to learn to code either Ruby or HTML + CSS (with a dash of jQuery) with other people. All skills levels are welcome! Coding is great skill to learn, but it does take time. I myself have struggling to put aside time to learn, and also to feel motivated to dedicate a few hours of my busy day to learning code. From going to courses and workshops, what I have taken away from the coding geniuses I have met is that developing a great community of fellow coders seriously increases your learning potential. Hopefully this is what this group will build! The idea is that a study group will gather in a pub or cafe (with free wifi) once a week and learn/improve their coding in a fun environment and make some new friends along the way. I'm no coding expert myself, and I will be teaching myself Ruby via codeacademy (https://www.codecademy.com/) and also improving my HTML + CSS via both codeacademy and personal projects. Once we all start developing our skills, collaborative projects will be explored. There will be two separate events, one for Ruby and one for HTML + CSS. Ruby will be on Monday evenings from 6:30pm - 9:30pm. HTML + CSS will be on Wednesday evenings from 6:30pm - 9:30pm. I am going to keep these groups small (15 people max) for now unless there is a massive interest. If there is, I will look into booking out spaces. If you have any questions, please feel free to send me a PM.

description:
Meet in person to share on a HTC Vive your Virtual Reality experiments :

• drafts of new VR experiences

• 3D models drafts ( procedural / hand-crafted / photogrammetry )

• new-mechanics, for the tracked-controllers, and for locomotion

• hobby ideas

• video-game alphas

• 3d-printed weapons

• VR extensions to game-engine-editors

• integrations (with Kinect, Intel 3D cameras, etc.)


The meetup is for "intermediate" and for "pro", only : after the summer, we will see whether to include segments for beginners.

No more hype, please: it's innovation time. No judgement allowed, only constructive feedback! When brain-storming, it is expected that a some ideas do not work, but our group's relaxed freedom guarantees a few cool surprises.

All demos will be verified in advanced as nausea-free.

After the summer, we will bring also Oculus/phones when the Touch-controllers/positional-head-tracking will arrive.

description:
This is an open group for anyone interested in the future of the Virtual Reality. 

VR is already a multi-billion dollar business and will bring so many possibilities into all sorts of different aspects of our lives from Gaming to Architecture, Health, Training, Education, Travel, Socialising and Social Media, Movies and Entertainment, Sports and Live Events, The Workplace and the Economy as a whole.

We're building a group (initially in London) for anyone working or interested in Virtual Reality (and AR / MR) including Entrepreneurs, Investors, Angels, Visionaries, Developers, Startups, Professionals, 360 Film Makers, infact anyone working in or wanting to be involved in the future of this exciting tech paradigm shift. We'll be holding regular meetups (starting with social drinks) to discuss the current tech and how we think it will evolve with an emphasis on where it is going from a business and commercial perspective. 

Lets see where it takes us.

description:
Glug is a series of events for the design and creative community. Our showcase event is held in London but there are now 10 other events around the world.

Based around a series of talks and informal networking, Glug has become one of the most exciting, credible and well attended creative events around.

Established in 2007, it’s an eclectic mix of people from all creative walks of life; from advertising, graphic design and the visual arts through to fashion, architecture and the crafts.

It’s a fine melting pot indeed, regularly attended by creatives, students, clients, cultural voyeurs, hipsters and the industry elite. Come! Be intoxicated and inspired, you’re also bound to make some new contacts, friends and maybe even find that next job/contract/lover.

Be part of the movement.

Check the videos here www.vimeo.com/glug, our website www.glugevents.com, Twitter and Facebook.

More Notworking than Networking™

About Go

The Go programming language is an open source project to make programmers more productive. Go is expressive, concise, clean, and efficient. Its concurrency mechanisms make it easy to write programs that get the most out of multicore and networked machines, while its novel type system enables flexible and modular program construction. Go compiles quickly to machine code yet has the convenience of garbage collection and the power of run-time reflection. It's a fast, statically typed, compiled language that feels like a dynamically typed, interpreted language.

description:
This is a group for any Senior Person, interested in lerning how to use their Laptop, Tablet or PC.
Would you like to learn how to do your shopping on line from Tescos, Sainsburys, Asda etc.
Would you like to learn how to use Skype so that you can talk to family members living abroad,
Perhaps you would like to learn how to do Online Banking, sort out your Pension etc..
I am offering Computer classes for beginners, in very small groups, so that you get good quality attention.

I am currently looking for a suitable venue to hold my classes. Classes will probably be in the Tottenham area of North London, with Seven Sisters ( Victoria Line) or Turnpike Lane ( Piccadilly Line) being the nearest stations.

Please let me know if you would prefer daytime or evening classes.

There will be a charge of £20.00 per session with each session being of 2 hours duration.

Silver Surfers must  bring their own laptop or Tablet to each sesssion as well as a note book, and pen or pencil.

In the meantime please email me with any questions you may have.

description: Welcome! We're Formisimo and User Conversion. description:
DevOps principles are being adopted by more organizations day after day. DevOps, however, focuses on the tools, hardware and software, rather than the actual humans who operate them. The health of your infrastructure is not just about hardware, software, automations and uptime - it also includes the health and wellbeing of your team.

HumanOps is a movement to to set additional principles which focus on the human aspects of running infrastructure. The HumanOps London meetup is a great  opportunity to discuss and share our experiences maintaining the good health of our teams. The event hosts 3-4 short presentations followed by networking chat over fresh snacks and drinks.

In order to keep this fun for everyone, we expect participants to follow our Code of Conduct.

description: Around Bristol, Bath and the West of England there are many companies and people working on the IoT and its technologies - from semiconductors through wireless communication via cloud services to big data analytics. In the locality we also have some interesting deployments of cutting edge IoT technologies. For example, Connecting Bristol is looking at how cities will evolve as the IoT gets deployed, and SPHERE is looking at connected healthcare. The Bristol and Bath IoT Meetup is a regular event where people working in, or with an interest in the IoT can get together to hear about new developments and activities, and to network with people involved with the IoT. The organisers want to encourage participation from people across the whole range of the IoT and for the Bristol and Bath IoT Meetup to be the place for IoT networking in the West of England. We want this to help enable collaboration and the development of business ideas in this growing sector. The format of the Meetup is that after an opportunity for some networking, the Meet Up will feature two or three short talks about topics relevant to the IoT (e.g. IoT security, wireless technology, sensor technology, analytic infrastructure, off-the-shelf IoT modules, …), followed by more networking.

description:
The London LabVIEW User Group (LLUG) is organised by Austin Consultants in collaboration with National Instruments. 

LabVIEW User Groups are a great way to stay connected with other LabVIEW users in your area, keep up to date with the latest developments in LabVIEW from National Instruments, and share best practice with other LabVIEW users. It is the perfect forum to discuss any challenges you may be having within a particular project or just within the LabVIEW programming environment. 

Using the London LabVIEW User Group forum on the National Instruments website and our group on Meetup.com you will be able to find dates for upcoming events, discuss subjects around LabVIEW and related tools, and provide feedback and suggestions for future topics at events. 

It really is a forum for the users, by the users, and the Austin Consultants team look forward to welcoming you at the next event. Visit the forum or join our Meet Up group to keep up to date with all the latest details and receive notifications about upcoming events.

description:
The TSC is excited to announce the second IMCreate Intelligent Mobility Hackathon. It will take place on the 4th and 5th of June at the Imovation Centre in Milton Keynes, England, United Kingdom.

Coders, business thinkers, technical experts and designers from academia and industry will compete for 24hrs to come up with the next big idea for transport, using a huge array of data sets and cutting edge hardware. The three best ideas from the event will go on to a showcase event at the Imagine Festival in June having had further time to develop their idea.

The first IMCreate was won by Team ‘Tubester’, consisting of Vladyslav Piskunov from Myintranet, Sam Li of AECOM and Sami Moustachir from Stratagem Technology. ‘Tubester’ used WIFI mapping and smartphone accelerometers to alert users when their tube stop is approaching, even though GPS is unavailable underground.

To sign up to the event ‘ImCreate2’ visit www.IMCreate.co.uk for more information.

description:
#CyberSec #InfoSec are key strategic priorities for the UK Government and critical to our future as a developed, connected nation with a service based economy.

description:
coinfest started in 2013 as a relatively small gathering of 100 or so Bitcoiners, celebrating the adoption of Bitcoin at a Waves Coffee House in Vancouver. 
It was conceived as a way to incentivize cryptocurrency acceptance while educating the public about its importance and use. Its popular success prompted the Bitcoiniacs (now CoinTrader) to place the worlds first Bitocin ATM there, which we again celebrated.

By 2014, CoinFest was growing in popularity, and that year it took a new direction: CoinFest spread across Canada and now internationally, exemplifying the border-defying and decentralized nature of crypto. 
Vancouver lead the way again by booking multiple venues simultaneously for a less centrally organized variety of exhibits, as Satoshi would have wanted. In 2015, CoinFest spread worldwide.

Now it is celebrated worldwide, with no real centre of authority. We hope you'll join the fun!

description: Calling all ‘aspiring’ entrepreneurs who feel stuck with getting their start-up off the ground. I’ve been working on this amazing eCommerce business idea for a couple of years now. For some reason I can’t seem to get it off the ground, as I keep losing money on the wrong companies/team to help me build this business up. Everyone you hire comes with a price tag. If they screw up, you are back to square one. Out of frustration, and never give up mentality, I’m starting this group to meet other ‘aspiring’ entrepreneurs who feel like I do. Why not be smart and gather our strengths together? Let’s get together and help each other out in areas where we lack the needed skills. For example, I’ve gained the skills to build a website in WordPress with the use of a Template. I can help you with this. Even if you just need somebody to brainstorm your idea’s with, we will be there for you. Let’s build our start-ups together. Go for it!

description: Leeds-based data expert The DataShed is bringing together specialists from across the UK to offer 20 Leeds developers the opportunity to become the city’s leading experts in Big Data at a lab event. Organised by The DataShed and global data and information system experts, cap hpi, the series of one day lab events aim to identify core opportunities in data analytics with hands on demonstrations and practical examples of the latest cutting edge data tools. The first event will see the developers exploring Apache Spark which is a fast and general engine for large-scale data processing. Hosted by cap hpi at Capitol House, Bond Court, Leeds, on 13th April, the lab event will showcase some of the newest big data tools and will teach developers practical skills such as how to build their own Hadoop cluster and how to use Apache Spark to fix data problems. All proceeds of the event will be donated to Leeds charities Candlelighters and St George’s Crypt. The day will involve a deep dive into Spark and associated technologies, which should help the attendees understand what’s possible with the tools – and whether it’s of relevance to their industry or business. Format of the day: • Setting up a Hadoop cluster on your laptop • Loading a dataset into Kafka • An opportunity to try out Spark Streaming, Spark SQL, and plug it into a few data visualisation tools To register for the event developers should email their details to hello@thedatashed.co.uk

description:
Le Wagon is a coding school for startups, creative people and tech entrepreneurs. 

Our main program, is a 9-week Full-Stack Coding Bootcamp, designed for complete beginners or "half-beginners" who really want to dive into programming and, above all, change their mindset. Learn to think like a developer, consider issues with new insight, and become more autonomous thanks to these newly acquired abilities. 

Our unique goal is to facilitate becoming an outstanding entrepreneur/developer who is able to code his/her own projects and to deeply understand technical issues. 

Le Wagon is was born in Paris in 2014 and now it's coming to London! We are a team of professional coaches (developers, designers, lean experts,...). 

In 2015, Le Wagon Paris ran four 9-week intensive camps; immersive coding bootcamps. Each time, 20+ entrepreneurs joined us from all around the world to learn to code and develop their startup MVP (= minimum viable product). 

Our first London bootcamp will start on 2nd July 2016 and the application process is now open - https://www.lewagon.com/apply/london

In addition to our intensive program, we organise free evening workshops during the week, open to everyone. Come & learn HTML, CSS, JavaScript and much more with us!
